a category you checked off.

00:07:11.960 --> 00:07:14.900
I was, for the most,
I was Korean American

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:16.070
and whatever that means.

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:23.370
For me, I actually went to
college at Northwestern.

00:07:23.370 --> 00:07:26.410
And being plucked from the
Bay Area to the Midwest

00:07:26.410 --> 00:07:28.439
was a bit of a
culture shock for me.

00:07:28.439 --> 00:07:30.230
A lot of things I took
for granted in terms

00:07:30.230 --> 00:07:32.074
of being with community.

00:07:32.074 --> 00:07:33.740
Stuff that I hadn't
really thought about

00:07:33.740 --> 00:07:35.840
before in terms of
being with a larger

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:37.160
Asian American community.

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:40.160
It suddenly became
very obvious to me

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:43.640
the things that I took for
granted in terms of the way

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:45.740
you interact with one another.

00:07:45.740 --> 00:07:52.160
And I look very different
from the people in my classes,

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:55.640
You and my interests are,
and what I grew up with,

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:58.646
these are very sort of
typical things I think.

00:07:58.646 --> 00:08:00.020
So it was a bit
of culture shock.

00:08:00.020 --> 00:08:02.311
And then the other thing was
that I took Asian American

00:08:02.311 --> 00:08:07.010
Studies courses in college,
which was just like for me,

00:08:07.010 --> 00:08:10.340
it was the beginning of a
lot of different things.

00:08:10.340 --> 00:08:14.930
It was a wake up call
in terms of my adapting

00:08:14.930 --> 00:08:17.157
Asian American as a
political identity.

00:08:17.157 --> 00:08:18.740
Not just something
that I checked off,

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:24.276
but something I purposely
wore on my sleeve.

00:08:24.276 --> 00:08:25.400
So now when people ask me--

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:27.750
I mean like it's clear
I'm like I'm Asian.

00:08:27.750 --> 00:08:31.650
But I'm usually asked, I'm
usually I'm Asian American.

00:08:31.650 --> 00:08:34.070
And then the other identity
is Korean American.

00:08:34.070 --> 00:08:36.860
But as a political identity,
what I wear on my sleeve,

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:38.419
it's definitely Asian American.

00:08:38.419 --> 00:08:41.210
And it's very purposeful
when I say that.

00:08:41.210 --> 00:08:44.570
Because I mean we've
already touched upon this,

00:08:44.570 --> 00:08:46.880
but like I think a lot
of people don't realize

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:50.000
they're Asian until
they get to like to--

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.180
in Asia, nobody really
considers themselves Asian.

00:08:53.180 --> 00:08:55.499
You're your own
whatever nationality

00:08:55.499 --> 00:08:56.540
where ever you come from.

00:08:56.540 --> 00:08:59.644
But when you come to
America, and a lot of people

00:08:59.644 --> 00:09:02.060
immigrate here, and suddenly
like this is thrust upon you.

00:09:02.060 --> 00:09:03.750
You're Asian whether
you like it or not.

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:08.930
And so however you embrace
that, it's up to you.

00:09:08.930 --> 00:09:10.490
So when you get
here, a lot of people

00:09:10.490 --> 00:09:14.330
are still resistant to
the idea of being Asian.

00:09:14.330 --> 00:09:20.900
But I think that as
an organizing tool,

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:25.730
Asian is a super inconvenient
convenient unwieldy term

00:09:25.730 --> 00:09:29.000
for a lot of different groups
and people, but very necessary.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.300
And so that's sort of, at
least from the beginning

00:09:32.300 --> 00:09:34.490
of my journey in college
when I sort of became aware

00:09:34.490 --> 00:09:40.010
as my history and my
identity, I think,

00:09:40.010 --> 00:09:42.300
where I wanted to-
and I decided--

00:09:42.300 --> 00:09:43.430
that's the thing.

00:09:43.430 --> 00:09:46.780
Being Asian, I think is Asian
American, it's an opt in.

00:09:46.780 --> 00:09:47.780
It's an opt in identity.

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:49.400
You have to opt in to
being Asian American.

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:51.800
You can go on being Chinese
American, Korean American,

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:53.610
or whatever.

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:58.820
But I think that you have to
choose to be Asian American.

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:01.640
VALARIE KAUR: Well, race
first came alive to me

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:04.070
through the stories
I grew up with.

00:10:04.070 --> 00:10:07.880
So my grandfather sailed on a
Japanese steamship, the Nippon

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:11.750
Maru, across the
Pacific Ocean in 1913.

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:13.260
He arrived in San Francisco.

00:10:13.260 --> 00:10:17.017
He was one of the first early
pioneers from South Asia.

00:10:17.017 --> 00:10:19.100
He was a Sikh American
wearing a turban and beard.

00:10:19.100 --> 00:10:21.950
And immigration officials
saw him on Angel Island

00:10:21.950 --> 00:10:24.650
and immediately
incarcerated him.

00:10:24.650 --> 00:10:28.340
Said there was no need for
his class of labor here.

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:32.060
And I actually cited prejudice
against his class of laborer

00:10:32.060 --> 00:10:34.530
for exhibiting
prejudice against him.

00:10:34.530 --> 00:10:38.480
So he was incarcerated
for months on end.

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:41.420
And it was a white
lawyer, Henry Marshall,

00:10:41.420 --> 00:10:44.300
who released him on a
writ of habeas corpus

00:10:44.300 --> 00:10:47.900
on Christmas Eve 1913.

00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:50.180
My grandfather made
his way down the valley

00:10:50.180 --> 00:10:52.880
and he settled in Clovis,
which is near Fresno,

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:55.190
just a few hours south of here.

00:10:55.190 --> 00:10:59.720
And I think something
about understanding the way

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:03.710
that that act of solidarity
set him free showed him what

00:11:03.710 --> 00:11:05.120
it meant to be an American.

00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:07.430
So when his Japanese
American neighbors were then

00:11:07.430 --> 00:11:09.800
rounded up and taken
to concentration camps

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:12.920
during World War II,
he was one of the few

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:14.420
who hooked up his
horse and buggy

00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:17.720
and traveled to the deserts of
post in Arizona to visit them.

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:19.730
He looks after
their farms and made

00:11:19.730 --> 00:11:22.310
sure they were safe
for when they returned.

00:11:22.310 --> 00:11:24.290
And so, growing up
with these stories,

00:11:24.290 --> 00:11:26.930
we still had like that piece of
petrified rock my grandfather

00:11:26.930 --> 00:11:29.665
found on that camp
sitting on our fireplace.

00:11:29.665 --> 00:11:31.040
So growing up with
these stories,

00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:32.956
I understood, just like
as Phil has mentioned,

00:11:32.956 --> 00:11:36.350
that growing up as Asian
American is an opt in.

00:11:36.350 --> 00:11:39.080
That my grandfather showed
me that saying that you're

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:41.402
Asian American is actually
an act of solidarity,

00:11:41.402 --> 00:11:42.860
that I will stand
with you brother,

00:11:42.860 --> 00:11:45.980
I will stand with you sister,
even if we are read differently

00:11:45.980 --> 00:11:47.720
by the dominant culture.

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:50.480
We are in this together.

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:52.400
I think race is a construct.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:54.080
But it's important
to think of it

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:58.070
as a cage that determines
how other people see us

00:11:58.070 --> 00:12:00.320
and how the state treats us.

00:12:00.320 --> 00:12:03.110
And so when my grandfather first
arrived, the cage we were under

00:12:03.110 --> 00:12:04.280
was Hindu.

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:06.140
And that wasn't even
a racial category.

00:12:06.140 --> 00:12:07.790
It was a religious
identification

00:12:07.790 --> 00:12:10.790
that didn't even align with my
grandfather's Sikh identity.

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:13.460
So we were called Hindus
when we first arrived.

00:12:13.460 --> 00:12:16.670
And then on census
forms, Hindus or other.

00:12:16.670 --> 00:12:18.620
And then under the
Asian Exclusion Acts,

00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:21.860
we, along with our Chinese,
Japanese American brothers

00:12:21.860 --> 00:12:25.250
and sisters were not allowed
to become citizens because we

00:12:25.250 --> 00:12:27.050
weren't Caucasian or white.

00:12:27.050 --> 00:12:28.420
We weren't allowed to own land.

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:30.420
And we weren't allowed
to return to this country

00:12:30.420 --> 00:12:31.700
if we ever left.

00:12:31.700 --> 00:12:34.490
There was a counterpart of my
grandfather's, Bhagat Singh

00:12:34.490 --> 00:12:38.690
Thind, who, in 1923, took a
case all the way to the Supreme

00:12:38.690 --> 00:12:42.170
Court arguing that actually
South Asian American are

00:12:42.170 --> 00:12:43.520
Caucasian.

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:45.920
And the Supreme Court said,
well, certainly our founders

00:12:45.920 --> 00:12:49.250
did not mean for you to
be on the same platform

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:52.580
as a white Scandinavian,
a blond Scandinavian.

00:12:52.580 --> 00:12:56.120
And so you are denied
citizenship along

00:12:56.120 --> 00:12:58.580
with other Asian Americans.

00:12:58.580 --> 00:13:01.929
So see how the concept of race
has shifted over the time.

00:13:01.929 --> 00:13:03.470
And so growing up
with these stories,

00:13:03.470 --> 00:13:06.350
I understood that this is
something that's imposed on us.

00:13:06.350 --> 00:13:10.190
That it's a cage that
we are operating under.

00:13:10.190 --> 00:13:13.430
I, myself, did not
experience it until I

00:13:13.430 --> 00:13:16.010
was a kid in elementary school.

00:13:16.010 --> 00:13:18.560
I was playing house
in the school yard

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:21.320
on my knees pretending to be a
baby, when a little boy ran up

00:13:21.320 --> 00:13:23.610
to me and said get
up you black dog.

00:13:23.610 --> 00:13:26.060
So here we are, a
family who's been called

00:13:26.060 --> 00:13:30.110
Hindu, other, Caucasian,
Asian, and now blackness

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:33.170
is something we have taken
on as the word, the N-word,

00:13:33.170 --> 00:13:37.280
and then Sand-N-word has
now been thrust upon us.

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:40.730
I did not understand the
danger and the violence

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:43.580
that racial constructs can
wield in our communities

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:45.500
until September 11th.

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:46.970
I was a 20-year-old college kid.

00:13:46.970 --> 00:13:49.520
I was here at Stanford.

00:13:49.520 --> 00:13:51.380
In the wake of the
terrorist attacks,

00:13:51.380 --> 00:13:54.530
hate violence erupted on city
streets across this country.

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:56.400
Four days later,
Balbir Singh Sodhi,

00:13:56.400 --> 00:13:58.730
who was a Sikh American
man, who was standing

00:13:58.730 --> 00:14:01.040
in front of his store
in Mesa, Arizona

00:14:01.040 --> 00:14:04.400
when a man wheeled around the
corner and shot him four times,

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:07.190
called himself a patriot
when he was arrested.

00:14:07.190 --> 00:14:09.050
Balbir Uncle was
someone my family knew.

00:14:09.050 --> 00:14:11.750
So I felt as though an
uncle had been murdered.

00:14:11.750 --> 00:14:14.540
And his murder barely
made the evening news.

00:14:14.540 --> 00:14:16.460
This was before Google.

00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:18.500
This was before
Facebook, before YouTube,

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:22.190
before Twitter, before we had
any modes of communication.

00:14:22.190 --> 00:14:24.920
And so the desperation
of understanding

00:14:24.920 --> 00:14:27.500
that a century of
being in this country,

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:31.070
we were still being read as
perpetually foreign, and now,

00:14:31.070 --> 00:14:32.630
and now, as terrorist.

00:14:32.630 --> 00:14:35.630
Because what's happened in
the years since September 11th

00:14:35.630 --> 00:14:38.600
is that a new racial
category has been formed,

00:14:38.600 --> 00:14:41.240
the racial category of
the Muslim terrorist.

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:44.030
And Muslims are in that
category, brown Muslims,

00:14:44.030 --> 00:14:50.630
black Muslims, Sikh Indians,
white Sikhs, Arab Christians,

00:14:50.630 --> 00:14:52.880
Latinos with beards,
Native Americans

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:56.450
have been killed in the name of
going back to their country out

00:14:56.450 --> 00:14:57.350
of Islamophobia.

00:14:57.350 --> 00:15:01.510
So this construct now is so
enormous that it cages so many

00:15:01.510 --> 00:15:02.650
of us.

00:15:02.650 --> 00:15:05.020
And my heartbreak
at this moment is

00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:07.930
that I thought that Balbir
Uncle's murder may turn me

00:15:07.930 --> 00:15:09.940
into an activist for 15 years.

00:15:09.940 --> 00:15:13.237
Every film, every lawsuit,
every social media campaign,

00:15:13.237 --> 00:15:15.070
I thought we were making
the country a safer

00:15:15.070 --> 00:15:17.530
place for the next generation.

00:15:17.530 --> 00:15:19.600
My son is born.

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:21.360
He's two years old.

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:23.792
And he's growing
up now in an era

00:15:23.792 --> 00:15:25.750
that the Southern Poverty
Law Center has called

00:15:25.750 --> 00:15:27.580
the era of enormous rage.

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:29.470
Hate crimes are
skyrocketing once again,

00:15:29.470 --> 00:15:32.200
rivaling the numbers
that we saw after 9/11.

00:15:32.200 --> 00:15:34.060
Hate groups have
increased in this country.

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:37.660
Anti-Muslim hate groups have
tripled in the last year.

00:15:37.660 --> 00:15:40.910
And the current
president is releasing

00:15:40.910 --> 00:15:44.400
an onslaught of executive
orders that punish our people.

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:46.110
I'm raising a brown
boy who may someday

00:15:46.110 --> 00:15:48.810
wear a turban as part of
his faith in a country that

00:15:48.810 --> 00:15:51.831
is more dangerous than
the one that I was given,

00:15:51.831 --> 00:15:54.330
even more dangerous than the
one that my grandfather arrived

00:15:54.330 --> 00:15:56.230
in a century ago.

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:59.010
So race is construct.

00:15:59.010 --> 00:16:00.680
Race is cage.

00:16:00.680 --> 00:16:04.170
And we don't understand
the danger of race

00:16:04.170 --> 00:16:06.810
until we listen to
one another's stories,

00:16:06.810 --> 00:16:09.120
until we understand that
Srinivas Kuchibhotla who

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:11.760
was murdered on February
22nd, Indian American, told

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:14.700
to go back to his country, is
not just a foreigner, not just

00:16:14.700 --> 00:16:17.550
an engineer immigrant.

00:16:17.550 --> 00:16:18.740
He's a brother.

00:16:18.740 --> 00:16:20.660
He's a fellow American.

00:16:20.660 --> 00:16:23.920
The Sikh American who
was shot in Washington

00:16:23.920 --> 00:16:26.310
fixing his car in
his own driveway

00:16:26.310 --> 00:16:29.580
was told to go back to
his country on March 3rd.

00:16:29.580 --> 00:16:31.380
He is a brother.

00:16:31.380 --> 00:16:35.940
But every time we hear a news
of ongoing violence, the one

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:39.480
thing that is giving me hope is
that there are millions of us--

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:41.395
we're having conversations
like this, right?

00:16:41.395 --> 00:16:43.770
There are millions of us now
who are politically awakened

00:16:43.770 --> 00:16:45.100
in ways that we haven't before.

00:16:45.100 --> 00:16:47.100
I feel like we've been
fighting this fight alone

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:49.860
for 15 years, 16 years, right?

00:16:49.860 --> 00:16:52.350
If all of you,
especially those who

00:16:52.350 --> 00:16:54.420
are in positions of
relative privilege

00:16:54.420 --> 00:16:56.760
can join us in this
fight, can show up,

00:16:56.760 --> 00:17:00.660
can exercise your voice
online and on the ground,

00:17:00.660 --> 00:17:04.380
then perhaps we can start
to come out from these cages

00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:07.829
and turn these cages into
platforms of solidarity.

00:17:07.829 --> 00:17:11.760
Thank you for inviting me
here to share this with you.

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:13.079
LORRIE MA: So I want to--

00:17:13.079 --> 00:17:14.849
before Quyen gets to go--

00:17:14.849 --> 00:17:17.410
I want to touch upon that a
little bit because I think,

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:20.839
Phil, you mentioned that you
sort of like Asian American

00:17:20.839 --> 00:17:23.329
is a political
identity of yours.

00:17:23.329 --> 00:17:26.579
And in this era, we're
getting sort of more active.

00:17:26.579 --> 00:17:30.540
But why is it so hard for Asian
Americans in terms of this race

00:17:30.540 --> 00:17:31.320
conversation?

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:33.469
Like why is activism
so difficult?

00:17:33.469 --> 00:17:34.510
Why do you think that is?

00:17:40.367 --> 00:17:42.825
QUYEN DINH: I really believe
that all politics is personal.

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:51.210
And the power of
moving beyond that cage

00:17:51.210 --> 00:17:57.980
and really making this decision
to claim your identity,

00:17:57.980 --> 00:18:02.610
that I am Vietnamese
American I am Asian American.

00:18:02.610 --> 00:18:05.320
I am a woman of color.

00:18:05.320 --> 00:18:09.080
Those things are not separate.

00:18:09.080 --> 00:18:11.340
They are all part of who I am.

00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:13.290
They are all part of my legacy.

00:18:13.290 --> 00:18:16.350
They are all part of
the pain and the trauma

00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:19.380
that my parents endured
as survivors of war

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:24.450
from the Vietnam War, as
warriors far, far beyond when

00:18:24.450 --> 00:18:28.080
we came here to
the United States.

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:36.240
And oftentimes, I reflect on
how much privilege is required

00:18:36.240 --> 00:18:39.490
to have this conversation.

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:42.910
Because if it weren't for UC
Berkeley and my Asian American

00:18:42.910 --> 00:18:46.690
Studies classes, I would
have not had this framework

00:18:46.690 --> 00:18:48.640
to understand race.

00:18:48.640 --> 00:18:51.010
I would not have had the
framework to understand

00:18:51.010 --> 00:18:56.110
how I am part of a historical
legacy of folks telling me

00:18:56.110 --> 00:19:00.960
who I am versus me
saying this is who I am

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:04.050
and claiming that as
self-determination for myself

00:19:04.050 --> 00:19:07.220
and for my community.

00:19:07.220 --> 00:19:11.890
And I really do agree that that
is the reason why these very

00:19:11.890 --> 00:19:15.880
personal conversations and
dialogues about how we are

00:19:15.880 --> 00:19:20.720
impacted by race is so critical
to that self-awareness, that

00:19:20.720 --> 00:19:24.700
politicization in being able
to have a conversation that

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:26.770
is really rooted in
understanding who you are

00:19:26.770 --> 00:19:27.940
and why you're here.

00:19:27.940 --> 00:19:32.350
And that is tremendous power
that we bring as new Americans

00:19:32.350 --> 00:19:35.030
to this country, redefining
what this country is.

00:19:39.098 --> 00:19:42.930
LORRIE MA: Phil, you looked
like you had something to say?

00:19:42.930 --> 00:19:44.680
PHIL YU: To answer
your question about why

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:52.895
is it so hard for Asian
Americans to become active,

00:19:52.895 --> 00:19:53.395
I suppose.

00:19:55.930 --> 00:19:58.500
I always say it's
like you can get

00:19:58.500 --> 00:20:05.230
Asians so hyped up about a new
kind of food or new restaurant.

00:20:05.230 --> 00:20:06.880
But like it's so
hard to make them

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:11.710
give a shit about everything
in terms of really

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:13.630
when it comes to
sort of speaking out

00:20:13.630 --> 00:20:16.150
about hate crimes and justice.

00:20:16.150 --> 00:20:18.430
There's an expectation
imposed on us

00:20:18.430 --> 00:20:21.439
that we're going to be the ones
who are going to be silent.

00:20:21.439 --> 00:20:22.855
We're going to be
the ones who are

00:20:22.855 --> 00:20:26.590
to keep our heads down, be the
good minorities, and not say.

00:20:26.590 --> 00:20:29.800
Even when it's well within
our right to do, so even when

00:20:29.800 --> 00:20:31.440
we should.

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:34.450
We should absolutely you
know kick down chairs,

00:20:34.450 --> 00:20:36.790
kick down walls, and like
say something, stand up.

00:20:36.790 --> 00:20:39.520
And I think that
there is so much--

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:43.090
a lot of our families
are immigrants.

00:20:43.090 --> 00:20:46.420
And they sacrificed so much
to get here the first place.

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:51.010
It is to speak out,
to say something,

00:20:51.010 --> 00:20:57.340
to make yourself
vulnerable in that way,

00:20:57.340 --> 00:20:59.486
it would seem contrary
to all the things--

00:20:59.486 --> 00:21:02.405
it would disrespect
all the sacrifices

00:21:02.405 --> 00:21:03.530
that were made to get here.

00:21:03.530 --> 00:21:08.350
But I do think that
not saying anything

00:21:08.350 --> 00:21:10.864
is disrespectful to all
the sacrifices, and all

00:21:10.864 --> 00:21:12.280
the challenges,
and all the things

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:13.779
that we had to
overcome to get here.

00:21:16.510 --> 00:21:18.250
And I think it's
just plain easier

00:21:18.250 --> 00:21:24.670
to try to sink in, try to blend
in, and lay back on privilege,

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:27.340
on this degree of privilege
that we have in this country.

00:21:30.760 --> 00:21:33.814
Sometimes it's just easier
to stay silent, you know?

00:21:33.814 --> 00:21:35.980
VALARIE KAUR: I want to
pick up on that because I've

00:21:35.980 --> 00:21:39.580
spent a lot of time with
Japanese American in Fresno who

00:21:39.580 --> 00:21:42.580
are now grandparents
and remembering

00:21:42.580 --> 00:21:46.000
what it was like to be interned
in those concentration camps.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.087
And Marion Masada, one of them--

00:21:48.087 --> 00:21:50.170
who has taught me to call
them concentration camps

00:21:50.170 --> 00:21:52.390
because that's what they were--

00:21:52.390 --> 00:21:54.880
has shared with me that
for many years after--

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:57.970
she was a little girl when she
was put in those camps with her

00:21:57.970 --> 00:21:58.810
family--

00:21:58.810 --> 00:22:00.520
and for many years
after their release,

00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:01.840
her parents didn't speak out.

00:22:01.840 --> 00:22:03.160
She didn't speak out.

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:05.764
And she likened it
to an act of incest.

00:22:05.764 --> 00:22:07.180
That here was a
nation that we had

00:22:07.180 --> 00:22:11.380
loved that committed an
act of such violation

00:22:11.380 --> 00:22:14.110
that there was confusion
and an inability

00:22:14.110 --> 00:22:18.040
to put language to the
violation that had taken place.

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:20.050
And so few stood
up for them then.

00:22:20.050 --> 00:22:21.700
So she turns to me
and says, Valarie, I

00:22:21.700 --> 00:22:24.304
will stand up for you now.

00:22:24.304 --> 00:22:27.700
What's giving me hope is that
the kind of courage that's

00:22:27.700 --> 00:22:30.040
required to stand
up to injustice

00:22:30.040 --> 00:22:32.230
means standing up
to state violence.

00:22:32.230 --> 00:22:35.290
We know that every time
the US government targets

00:22:35.290 --> 00:22:38.470
a particular community, not
for not for what they've done,

00:22:38.470 --> 00:22:42.400
but for who they are, it
emboldens ordinary people

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:45.010
to act on biases within them
and target those communities.

00:22:45.010 --> 00:22:49.270
So every time we see the state
punish particular communities

00:22:49.270 --> 00:22:51.940
through detentions,
deportations, surveillance,

00:22:51.940 --> 00:22:54.227
threats of torture,
we see hate crimes

00:22:54.227 --> 00:22:55.560
against those communities go up.

00:22:55.560 --> 00:22:56.710
We've seen since 9/11.

00:22:56.710 --> 00:22:59.440
We saw it since World War II.

00:22:59.440 --> 00:23:01.780
And that means that if
we, as Asian Americans,

00:23:01.780 --> 00:23:04.480
are going to stand up to try
to make our community safer,

00:23:04.480 --> 00:23:06.610
it means speaking
truth to power.

00:23:06.610 --> 00:23:07.330
Right?

00:23:07.330 --> 00:23:11.295
Muslim Ban 2.0 is coming down
tomorrow, everybody, March 16.

00:23:11.295 --> 00:23:12.295
It's happening tomorrow.

00:23:13.270 --> 00:23:18.070
I know I am bracing for more
violence against my people.

00:23:18.070 --> 00:23:20.977
Not only the refugees and the
immigrants whose lives are now,

00:23:20.977 --> 00:23:22.810
and futures are now
going to be in jeopardy,

00:23:22.810 --> 00:23:24.670
but here in our
country Americans,

00:23:24.670 --> 00:23:27.530
children in schoolyards, I
am worried for their safety.

00:23:27.530 --> 00:23:29.822
They're worried for
their own safety.

00:23:29.822 --> 00:23:31.900
Every week I'm at a
different college campus.

00:23:31.900 --> 00:23:35.350
I just got back from University
of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.

00:23:35.350 --> 00:23:38.680
And the students came up to
me with heartbreaking stories

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:42.580
of bullying, of racial violence,
of even sexual violence,

00:23:42.580 --> 00:23:44.680
their inability to
make sense of it.

00:23:44.680 --> 00:23:47.151
These are not captured
by hate crime statistics.

00:23:47.151 --> 00:23:49.150
The hate crimes are just
the tip of the iceberg.

00:23:49.150 --> 00:23:51.640
What remains invisible
beneath the surface

00:23:51.640 --> 00:23:55.419
is what it feels like to live
in a climate of hate and fear.

00:23:55.419 --> 00:23:57.460
And we have a new generation
rising up like that.

00:23:57.460 --> 00:23:57.850
Right?

00:23:57.850 --> 00:24:00.100
They don't remember what it
was like before 9/11, Phil.

00:24:00.100 --> 00:24:00.600
We do.

00:24:00.600 --> 00:24:03.590
We have that like moral
resource, but they don't.

00:24:03.590 --> 00:24:05.470
The shadow of 9/11
is so long, people

00:24:05.470 --> 00:24:08.290
don't even realize we're
standing in the shadow.

00:24:08.290 --> 00:24:11.470
And so what it takes is courage
to stand up to state violence.

00:24:11.470 --> 00:24:15.310
And this is why you naming
warrior hood I think

00:24:15.310 --> 00:24:16.720
is like a sister yes.

00:24:16.720 --> 00:24:19.120
Like me standing with
you was warrior sister.

00:24:19.120 --> 00:24:21.850
Because I think for Asian
American communities,

00:24:21.850 --> 00:24:25.180
we inherit traditions
that we think

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:27.220
we're just supposed to
preserve and interpret

00:24:27.220 --> 00:24:29.230
as our parents did and pass on.

00:24:29.230 --> 00:24:31.660
But actually, our religious,
our cultural heritages,

00:24:31.660 --> 00:24:32.860
they are living.

00:24:32.860 --> 00:24:35.280
They are alive and it's up
to us to reinterpret them

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:37.180
for a new time.

00:24:37.180 --> 00:24:39.040
And so my call
right now is I want

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:41.580
a new generation of Sikh and
South Asian and Asian American

00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:43.630
activists to rise
up as warriors.

00:24:43.630 --> 00:24:46.170
And the story tells the
story of Mai Bhago who

00:24:46.170 --> 00:24:49.810
was the first Sikh woman warrior
in the 17th century in South

00:24:49.810 --> 00:24:50.710
Asia.

00:24:50.710 --> 00:24:52.690
The story goes there
were 40 soldiers who

00:24:52.690 --> 00:24:55.160
abandoned their post
during a great battle.

00:24:55.160 --> 00:24:56.410
They came back to the village.

00:24:56.410 --> 00:24:59.350
They said the fight is too hard,
we can't go back out there.

00:24:59.350 --> 00:25:03.400
And this village woman, woman,
woman of color, turns to them

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:08.180
and says no, no, you will
return to the battle.

00:25:08.180 --> 00:25:10.640
And I will lead you.

00:25:10.640 --> 00:25:11.840
She mounts a horse.

00:25:11.840 --> 00:25:13.910
She dons a turban with
a sword in her hand,

00:25:13.910 --> 00:25:16.490
with fire in her eyes,
she leads them back

00:25:16.490 --> 00:25:19.100
into the flames when
no one else would.

00:25:19.100 --> 00:25:22.520
She becomes the one
she is waiting for.

00:25:22.520 --> 00:25:24.230
I tell that story
because I think

00:25:24.230 --> 00:25:25.690
there is an impulse to desert.

00:25:25.690 --> 00:25:28.160
There is an impulse to give
up, to keep our head down,

00:25:28.160 --> 00:25:30.170
to play it safe.

00:25:30.170 --> 00:25:32.780
But if we can call forth
the warriors within us

00:25:32.780 --> 00:25:35.390
to take our hands
and lead us back

00:25:35.390 --> 00:25:38.180
into the fire,
that's the only way

00:25:38.180 --> 00:25:42.961
our generation will fight
the good fight here and now.

00:25:42.961 --> 00:25:48.620
QUYEN DINH: And I think
I'm reflecting on,

00:25:48.620 --> 00:25:51.500
I'm reflecting on
just how hard it

00:25:51.500 --> 00:25:55.880
is for my parents to share
their experience surviving

00:25:55.880 --> 00:25:58.790
the Vietnam War.

00:25:58.790 --> 00:26:04.230
In this room, how many of
you, how many of your parents,

00:26:04.230 --> 00:26:08.270
were the first ones
to come to the US?

00:26:08.270 --> 00:26:12.500
And in this room, how
many of those parents

00:26:12.500 --> 00:26:17.740
came because of fleeing
some sort of trauma,

00:26:17.740 --> 00:26:20.721
political trauma, religious
trauma, economic trauma,

00:26:20.721 --> 00:26:21.220
poverty?

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:29.480
We come from
communities-- and by we,

00:26:29.480 --> 00:26:32.255
I want to talk from my own
experience being Vietnamese

00:26:32.255 --> 00:26:34.850
American--

00:26:34.850 --> 00:26:38.570
I come from a family
who has survived

00:26:38.570 --> 00:26:42.840
bombings in their countries.

00:26:42.840 --> 00:26:47.940
My parents got on a boat, sailed
across the South China Seas,

00:26:47.940 --> 00:26:49.720
ended up in Malaysia.

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:53.420
And I was born in New Orleans.

00:26:53.420 --> 00:26:58.550
And for my entire life, the
story of the Vietnam War

00:26:58.550 --> 00:27:03.090
was rarely ever told.

00:27:03.090 --> 00:27:05.700
And when my political
moment was actually

00:27:05.700 --> 00:27:08.820
going to Washington
DC for the first time

00:27:08.820 --> 00:27:13.830
as a high school senior, what
I was so stoked about seeing

00:27:13.830 --> 00:27:16.600
was the Vietnam War Memorial.

00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:18.970
Because this memorial
to me represented

00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:22.160
why I was here in America.

00:27:22.160 --> 00:27:27.690
And as I got there, I looked
at the Smiths and the Jones

00:27:27.690 --> 00:27:30.090
and the Derricks and the Johns.

00:27:30.090 --> 00:27:33.510
And I was looking for
the Dinhs, and the Trans,

00:27:33.510 --> 00:27:36.670
and the Nguyens, and
the Ngos, and the Phams.

00:27:36.670 --> 00:27:40.910
I was looking for all
the Vietnamese soldiers

00:27:40.910 --> 00:27:46.550
who sacrificed their lives
in this fight for freedom.

00:27:46.550 --> 00:27:50.260
And I started to get
really, really angry.

00:27:50.260 --> 00:27:53.880
And I started to think about all
the children, all the people,

00:27:53.880 --> 00:27:58.300
all the families, who died
in Vietnam who were really

00:27:58.300 --> 00:28:02.740
pawns in wars, and why their
names weren't reflected

00:28:02.740 --> 00:28:05.640
on this wall.

00:28:05.640 --> 00:28:08.230
And I went back and talked
with my high school teacher

00:28:08.230 --> 00:28:10.990
while everyone else was
at the museum gift shop.

00:28:10.990 --> 00:28:13.780
And I just started bawling
and sharing with him

00:28:13.780 --> 00:28:16.970
how confused I
felt, because I felt

00:28:16.970 --> 00:28:19.460
so indebted to these
American soldiers who

00:28:19.460 --> 00:28:22.100
had sacrificed their
lives and their families

00:28:22.100 --> 00:28:24.170
for me to be here.

00:28:24.170 --> 00:28:27.180
And yet, at the same
time, I felt so invisible.

00:28:29.910 --> 00:28:32.720
And I felt betrayed.

00:28:32.720 --> 00:28:34.790
And I didn't have
the words to express

00:28:34.790 --> 00:28:36.350
what I was feeling at the time.

00:28:36.350 --> 00:28:39.260
And I think going to
Berkeley and getting

00:28:39.260 --> 00:28:41.540
my political
education I realized

00:28:41.540 --> 00:28:45.850
this was the first time that I
felt marginalized in my country

00:28:45.850 --> 00:28:47.990
where I felt like
this is not home.

00:28:47.990 --> 00:28:49.850
And it was that
moment that led me

00:28:49.850 --> 00:28:54.950
on my journey to really reclaim
what it is that who I am

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:59.180
and the history, the people,
the historical forces that

00:28:59.180 --> 00:29:00.800
brought me here today.

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:02.750
And I think that's
the reason why

00:29:02.750 --> 00:29:07.720
I am so passionate about
this work is because advocacy

00:29:07.720 --> 00:29:09.950
is personal to me.

00:29:09.950 --> 00:29:12.650
When I look at the
deportation orders,

00:29:12.650 --> 00:29:17.300
I think about my cousin who
came as a teenager to the US

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:18.920
with a criminal
conviction record

00:29:18.920 --> 00:29:22.910
because there was no support
at home, no support at schools.

00:29:22.910 --> 00:29:26.470
And he has a deportation
order to Vietnam.

00:29:26.470 --> 00:29:28.940
There are 15,000 other
Southeast Asian Americans

00:29:28.940 --> 00:29:32.240
who have this same experience
and yet is not talked about.

00:29:32.240 --> 00:29:34.490
When we talk about the
Affordable Care Act being taken

00:29:34.490 --> 00:29:38.930
away, I think about my dad
who got ACA health insurance

00:29:38.930 --> 00:29:41.090
coverage for the first time.

00:29:41.090 --> 00:29:45.560
And I think about my cousins
who just came to the US

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:46.700
from Vietnam.

00:29:46.700 --> 00:29:48.560
Who, because they
live in California,

00:29:48.560 --> 00:29:51.560
are eligible to access
Affordable Care Act and health

00:29:51.560 --> 00:29:56.030
care plans because we
expanded coverage for newly

00:29:56.030 --> 00:29:58.070
arrived immigrant communities.

00:29:58.070 --> 00:30:01.460
All of these policies
are so personal to me.

00:30:01.460 --> 00:30:07.130
And I think when we each have
that moment of connection,

00:30:07.130 --> 00:30:13.000
that's when you're able to see
a shift in how we understand

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:16.930
ourselves and how we understand
exercising our power by raising

00:30:16.930 --> 00:30:18.640
our voices and by
being who we are.

00:30:21.450 --> 00:30:23.490
VALARIE KAUR: I am so
moved by your moment

00:30:23.490 --> 00:30:25.750
at the Vietnam Memorial.

00:30:25.750 --> 00:30:27.660
And I want to share
with you, I think

00:30:27.660 --> 00:30:31.590
what it tells us is the
importance of historical memory

00:30:31.590 --> 00:30:35.970
and storytelling and
our charge for here now.

00:30:35.970 --> 00:30:38.490
Because I had that
moment, my moment

00:30:38.490 --> 00:30:44.310
was the 9/11 Memorial where
I have only gone for moments.

00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:48.810
Because just as I mourn the
3,000 people who were killed,

00:30:48.810 --> 00:30:49.860
I stand at the fountain.

00:30:49.860 --> 00:30:52.470
I feel the spray of
the water at my face.

00:30:52.470 --> 00:30:55.470
I run my hands over their names.

00:30:55.470 --> 00:30:58.500
But in the museum and
at the memorial itself,

00:30:58.500 --> 00:31:01.980
there is not a
moment of recognition

00:31:01.980 --> 00:31:05.220
for all the violence that was
done in the aftermath of 9/11.

00:31:05.220 --> 00:31:06.810
So it's like I
grieve my community.

00:31:06.810 --> 00:31:08.410
I grieve my country.

00:31:08.410 --> 00:31:11.760
And I want to be able to own
this narrative completely

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:13.980
but I felt invisible.

00:31:13.980 --> 00:31:17.550
That changed this
last 9/11 anniversary.

00:31:17.550 --> 00:31:21.480
I had a woman Carrie Kelly
who lost her stepfather

00:31:21.480 --> 00:31:24.930
in the towers, he was
a fireman, invited

00:31:24.930 --> 00:31:27.270
me to come and grieve with her.

00:31:27.270 --> 00:31:28.941
And oh, I grieved.

00:31:28.941 --> 00:31:30.690
There was something
in me that broke open.

00:31:30.690 --> 00:31:33.300
And I was just sobbing,
because I realized for 15 years

00:31:33.300 --> 00:31:37.050
I had not been given
permission to grieve on 9/11.

00:31:37.050 --> 00:31:39.690
Because from that moment,
I had to work to protect

00:31:39.690 --> 00:31:41.430
my community from being killed.

00:31:41.430 --> 00:31:43.740
So she gave me permission to
enter that grief with her.

00:31:43.740 --> 00:31:45.323
And then she did
something remarkable.

00:31:45.323 --> 00:31:48.300
She said, let me come with you
to the memorial of Balbir Singh

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:50.190
Sodhi in Arizona.

00:31:50.190 --> 00:31:51.680
And so she traveled with me.

00:31:51.680 --> 00:31:56.040
And the 9/11 Memorial,
the whole world knows.

00:31:56.040 --> 00:32:00.390
The memorial that lies at the
corner of a Chevron gas station

00:32:00.390 --> 00:32:02.590
in Arizona nobody knows.

00:32:02.590 --> 00:32:05.110
It's the spot where Balbir
Uncle bled to death.

00:32:05.110 --> 00:32:07.290
And there's a tiny
plaque in the corner.

00:32:07.290 --> 00:32:10.770
And I see this place as
the second ground zero.

00:32:10.770 --> 00:32:13.530
It is the ground zero for
every single person who

00:32:13.530 --> 00:32:17.179
was killed in reaction to
9/11, not just in hate crimes,

00:32:17.179 --> 00:32:19.470
but in the wars abroad--
civilians and soldiers alike--

00:32:19.470 --> 00:32:21.270
it is a second ground zero.

00:32:21.270 --> 00:32:24.480
And I stood at that spot and
I put roses on the ground

00:32:24.480 --> 00:32:26.820
next to his brother Rana Sodhi.

00:32:26.820 --> 00:32:28.860
And Ranajeet turned to me--

00:32:28.860 --> 00:32:31.680
this was just in
September, September 15.

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:35.220
And he said 15 years
and nothing has changed.

00:32:35.220 --> 00:32:36.990
And I asked him,
Ranajeet, what is the one

00:32:36.990 --> 00:32:38.700
thing we have not tried yet?

00:32:38.700 --> 00:32:40.470
Who is the one person
we have not tried

00:32:40.470 --> 00:32:42.840
to extend our love to yet?

00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:46.200
And we said, it's the murderer.

00:32:46.200 --> 00:32:47.670
It's the person
who took his life--

00:32:47.670 --> 00:32:52.300
Frank Roque-- who is lingering
in a prison some miles away.

00:32:52.300 --> 00:32:54.240
And so, out of
desperation almost,

00:32:54.240 --> 00:32:56.370
we do something
that was unthinkable

00:32:56.370 --> 00:33:01.320
before, we called the prison
the next morning to talk

00:33:01.320 --> 00:33:03.600
to Balbir Sodhi's murderer.

00:33:03.600 --> 00:33:07.860
And in the beginning, I think
it's a complete disaster.

00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:09.750
Frank says, yes,
I'm sorry for what

00:33:09.750 --> 00:33:11.640
happened on 9/11-- on 9/15.

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:13.940
But I'm also sorry for all
the people who died on 9/11.

00:33:13.940 --> 00:33:17.370
And at this moment I think
there are limits to love.

00:33:17.370 --> 00:33:20.520
How dare I think
that I could engage

00:33:20.520 --> 00:33:22.890
in this moment of
reconciliation now?

00:33:22.890 --> 00:33:26.310
And Rana Sodhi, he
hears what I can't.

00:33:26.310 --> 00:33:28.050
He says, Frank, this
is the first time

00:33:28.050 --> 00:33:30.810
I've ever heard you
say you were sorry.

00:33:30.810 --> 00:33:32.610
He takes a step toward Frank.

00:33:32.610 --> 00:33:34.020
Frank takes a step toward him.

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:35.970
He says, yes, I am sorry.

00:33:35.970 --> 00:33:39.720
I'm sorry for what I did
to you and your family.

00:33:39.720 --> 00:33:42.500
And when I go to heaven
to be judged by God,

00:33:42.500 --> 00:33:44.670
I will ask to see your uncle.

00:33:44.670 --> 00:33:49.960
And I will hug him and I
will ask for his forgiveness.

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:54.960
And Rana Sodhi says, we
have already forgiven you.

00:33:54.960 --> 00:33:58.810
I tell that story
because the only reason

00:33:58.810 --> 00:34:03.750
anyone knows it is because
we posted it online.

00:34:03.750 --> 00:34:06.370
The time of Vietnam,
and even at the time

00:34:06.370 --> 00:34:08.050
when September 11th
first happened,

00:34:08.050 --> 00:34:11.230
we did not have the open
and free internet and all

00:34:11.230 --> 00:34:14.020
the platforms we have to
tell our community stories.

00:34:14.020 --> 00:34:17.290
Historical memory was owned by
the powerful few that framed

00:34:17.290 --> 00:34:20.020
whose lives were grievable
and whose weren't.

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:21.580
And now we have tools.

00:34:21.580 --> 00:34:24.310
We have tools to tell the
stories of those who you

00:34:24.310 --> 00:34:25.570
are defending in deportations.

00:34:25.570 --> 00:34:28.480
We have tools to tell Rana
Sodhi's story and his act

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:30.070
of revolutionary love.

00:34:30.070 --> 00:34:31.659
We have tools now,
I can tell you

00:34:31.659 --> 00:34:35.110
this is a second ground zero
to remember, to claim, as a way

00:34:35.110 --> 00:34:36.881
to continue to fight
the good fight.

00:34:36.881 --> 00:34:39.380
And so what you are doing here,
with the revolution that you

00:34:39.380 --> 00:34:41.993
are all part of, and
giving communities voice

00:34:41.993 --> 00:34:44.409
through Google and through all
the initiatives you support

00:34:44.409 --> 00:34:47.110
is actually part of the
movement for social justice

00:34:47.110 --> 00:34:47.860
in this country.

00:34:47.860 --> 00:34:49.090
It means the world to us.

00:34:49.090 --> 00:34:51.074
[APPLAUSE]

00:34:56.045 --> 00:34:56.920
LORRIE MA: All right.

00:34:56.920 --> 00:34:58.740
Let's get the round of applause.

00:34:58.740 --> 00:35:03.040
So growing up, so I'm actually--
not many people know this--

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:04.234
but I grew up in China.

00:35:04.234 --> 00:35:05.650
So I was born and
raised in China.

00:35:05.650 --> 00:35:07.280
And I came here when I was 10.

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:11.540
And I was severely bullied in
school because I was different.

00:35:11.540 --> 00:35:14.260
And one of the things
that growing up I was told

00:35:14.260 --> 00:35:17.320
was if you just kept your
head down and just kept

00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:19.810
doing what you were
doing, just stay silent,

00:35:19.810 --> 00:35:21.860
you would just get through
this, and it's fine.

00:35:21.860 --> 00:35:24.790
And this is something that
culturally was ingrained in me

00:35:24.790 --> 00:35:29.140
to just be this sort of
silent model minority.

00:35:29.140 --> 00:35:32.410
And my parents built their
success on the back of this,

00:35:32.410 --> 00:35:34.720
just being silent, not
airing your "dirty laundry"

00:35:34.720 --> 00:35:36.800
quote unquote, and
sort of staying

00:35:36.800 --> 00:35:39.550
in this little confinement.

00:35:39.550 --> 00:35:42.370
And a lot of people
actually, stereotypically,

00:35:42.370 --> 00:35:44.920
feel that the success
of Asian American

00:35:44.920 --> 00:35:46.870
is because they are
sort of this model

00:35:46.870 --> 00:35:50.050
minority and this silent,
invisible population.

00:35:50.050 --> 00:35:51.910
How do you reconcile
that with some

00:35:51.910 --> 00:35:54.670
of the things that are happening
today and some of the activism

00:35:54.670 --> 00:35:56.130
that you're sort
of advocating for?

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:02.720
PHIL YU: I mean for me,
look, the number one question

00:36:02.720 --> 00:36:07.220
I get about my work, And
it's like why did you

00:36:07.220 --> 00:36:09.500
call your blog Angry Asian Man?

00:36:09.500 --> 00:36:13.012
Like what made you so angry?

00:36:13.012 --> 00:36:14.720
Was there some inciting
moment like that?

00:36:14.720 --> 00:36:15.790
And it really wasn't.

00:36:15.790 --> 00:36:19.760
It really was just
coming on my own

00:36:19.760 --> 00:36:22.970
this journey that I
was having towards

00:36:22.970 --> 00:36:25.400
some sort of Asian American
political consciousness

00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:28.744
through school, through
Asian American Studies.

00:36:28.744 --> 00:36:31.160
So there wasn't any one-- like
I wasn't a victim of a hate

00:36:31.160 --> 00:36:32.960
crime, and I was
like, oh, so mad I've

00:36:32.960 --> 00:36:35.210
got to go to my computer
and start writing.

00:36:35.210 --> 00:36:39.664
But if I look back-- so I
always tell people that--

00:36:39.664 --> 00:36:44.370
but I look back and
it's called Angry Asian

00:36:44.370 --> 00:36:46.170
Man because that is so--

00:36:46.170 --> 00:36:51.000
that idea of angry Asian
anything is so in the face of,

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:53.670
it's so contrary to the
perception of Asians

00:36:53.670 --> 00:36:55.260
in this country in the West.

00:36:55.260 --> 00:36:59.010
It's like we're supposed to
be this the silent, the quiet

00:36:59.010 --> 00:36:59.760
types.

00:36:59.760 --> 00:37:02.850
The ones who don't raise our
voice, the ones who don't say

00:37:02.850 --> 00:37:04.080
anything, and don't speak up.

00:37:04.080 --> 00:37:05.340
And I was like I
just wanted something

00:37:05.340 --> 00:37:07.560
that was confrontational,
that was provocative.

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:08.976
And so when people
visit the site,

00:37:08.976 --> 00:37:11.520
they see that it's like it's
an affront to their senses,

00:37:11.520 --> 00:37:14.186
angry Asian.

00:37:14.186 --> 00:37:15.810
But when I look back
at my own journey,

00:37:15.810 --> 00:37:17.670
I think there was
really one inciting--

00:37:17.670 --> 00:37:19.200
there was an inciting moment.

00:37:19.200 --> 00:37:23.040
The one that really sort
of lit a fire and made me

00:37:23.040 --> 00:37:28.590
realize that I was a part of
a tradition that was already

00:37:28.590 --> 00:37:30.210
existed of Asian
American activism,

00:37:30.210 --> 00:37:31.543
of people who were speaking out.

00:37:33.890 --> 00:37:36.300
It was when I learned about
the murder of Vincent Chin.

00:37:36.300 --> 00:37:38.800
Do people here know
who Vincent Chin was?

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:41.220
Just a show of hands,
I want to just--

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:44.820
So for people who don't
know, Vincent Chin in 1982,

00:37:44.820 --> 00:37:46.850
he was in Detroit, this
Chinese American guy.

00:37:46.850 --> 00:37:48.630
He was out for his
bachelor party.

00:37:48.630 --> 00:37:51.080
He was going to get married
in a couple of days.

00:37:51.080 --> 00:37:52.913
He ends up getting in
an argument with a guy

00:37:52.913 --> 00:37:56.760
at a strip club for
his bachelor party.

00:37:56.760 --> 00:38:00.667
And the witnesses remember
overhearing the man saying

00:38:00.667 --> 00:38:02.250
to Vincent, it's
because of you mother

00:38:02.250 --> 00:38:03.780
fuckers that we're out of work.

00:38:03.780 --> 00:38:10.560
And he was referring
to auto jobs being

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:12.230
lost to Japanese manufacturers.

00:38:12.230 --> 00:38:14.100
They were in Detroit.

00:38:14.100 --> 00:38:15.390
And the fight breaks out.

00:38:15.390 --> 00:38:18.600
And Vincent Chin ends up
getting killed with a baseball

00:38:18.600 --> 00:38:20.840
bat, his head bashed in.

00:38:20.840 --> 00:38:22.980
Goes into a coma and
dies three days later.

00:38:22.980 --> 00:38:26.960
Learning about this
case-- and so this case

00:38:26.960 --> 00:38:28.830
it was about a hate
crime, but it was also

00:38:28.830 --> 00:38:31.620
about the demand for
justice that swelled up

00:38:31.620 --> 00:38:36.900
from a Pan Asian movement
fighting for justice

00:38:36.900 --> 00:38:39.240
for Vincent Chin and
against his killers.

00:38:39.240 --> 00:38:42.254
I learned about the case
nearly 20 years after the fact

00:38:42.254 --> 00:38:43.170
when I was in college.

00:38:43.170 --> 00:38:46.890
And I honestly when I learned
about it, for my first instinct

00:38:46.890 --> 00:38:48.239
was to get really angry.

00:38:48.239 --> 00:38:50.530
Not only because of what
happened and the circumstances

00:38:50.530 --> 00:38:51.030
of the case.

00:38:51.030 --> 00:38:52.900
That is infuriating.

00:38:52.900 --> 00:38:56.110
But because like why haven't
I heard about this before?

00:38:56.110 --> 00:38:57.930
Why am I only learning
about this now?

00:38:57.930 --> 00:39:00.060
Like this is something
that is part of my history,

00:39:00.060 --> 00:39:03.960
because it swelled up in me
just this idea of every moment

00:39:03.960 --> 00:39:06.390
where someone called
me a racial slur,

00:39:06.390 --> 00:39:09.210
where I was made to feel like
I did not belong in the country

00:39:09.210 --> 00:39:11.477
that I was born in.

00:39:11.477 --> 00:39:12.810
All that sort of just welled up.

00:39:12.810 --> 00:39:19.860
And I realized it's like this
idea of finding your voice,

00:39:19.860 --> 00:39:23.054
raising your voice, and
getting angry about something.

00:39:23.054 --> 00:39:24.720
That was something I
had not been taught

00:39:24.720 --> 00:39:27.660
by suppressing some of
these histories that

00:39:27.660 --> 00:39:29.170
were relevant to me.

00:39:29.170 --> 00:39:31.080
The history of civil
rights in this country

00:39:31.080 --> 00:39:34.260
is amazing, and incredible,
and we owe a debt

00:39:34.260 --> 00:39:36.530
to that as Asian American.

00:39:36.530 --> 00:39:40.130
But so many people have taught
me that where's my place?

00:39:40.130 --> 00:39:43.320
Like I'm absent
from that, you know?

00:39:43.320 --> 00:39:45.900
At least that's what was
sort of taught in my way.

00:39:45.900 --> 00:39:47.070
And I was like no, no, no.

00:39:47.070 --> 00:39:49.744
There is a history of activism
amongst Asian Americans

00:39:49.744 --> 00:39:50.410
in this country.

00:39:50.410 --> 00:39:54.540
And so I realize that there is
this idea of us being quiet,

00:39:54.540 --> 00:39:59.070
because it kind of
suppresses this identity

00:39:59.070 --> 00:40:00.870
that we are allowed
to have, that we're

00:40:00.870 --> 00:40:03.570
allowed to be part of
the things that shape

00:40:03.570 --> 00:40:05.340
and mold this country.

00:40:05.340 --> 00:40:07.742
And I'm talking about when
people holler and get mad

00:40:07.742 --> 00:40:09.450
and get angry about
stuff, because that's

00:40:09.450 --> 00:40:12.230
when shit gets done, you know?

00:40:12.230 --> 00:40:14.480
VALARIE KAUR: So I'm the
director of the Revolutionary

00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:15.740
Love Project.

00:40:15.740 --> 00:40:19.010
And I love Angry Asian Man.

00:40:19.010 --> 00:40:19.850
I love you.

00:40:19.850 --> 00:40:22.427
And I also love the platform
and I love the name.

00:40:22.427 --> 00:40:23.635
PHIL YU: Please call me Phil.

00:40:23.635 --> 00:40:25.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:28.252 --> 00:40:30.710
VALARIE KAUR: I think that
anger has such an important role

00:40:30.710 --> 00:40:33.110
in our movements, a vital role.

00:40:33.110 --> 00:40:37.520
And as Asian Americans, but also
as women, and as Asian women,

00:40:37.520 --> 00:40:40.370
and South Asian women,
we are consistently

00:40:40.370 --> 00:40:45.290
taught to bury our rage,
to suffocate our anger,

00:40:45.290 --> 00:40:47.870
to compromise, to
sacrifice, for the good

00:40:47.870 --> 00:40:52.040
of the family, or the wider
community, or the country.

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:54.230
When I define
revolutionary love, what

00:40:54.230 --> 00:40:56.134
makes it revolutionary
is that we

00:40:56.134 --> 00:40:58.550
are extending-- we're thinking
about love not as a passing

00:40:58.550 --> 00:41:00.080
feeling, but as a commitment.

00:41:00.080 --> 00:41:01.550
As a commitment
to extend our will

00:41:01.550 --> 00:41:04.040
for the flourishing
of others, even

00:41:04.040 --> 00:41:05.824
our opponents, and ourselves.

00:41:05.824 --> 00:41:08.240
And when we love in the face
of fear, or rage, or vitriol,

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:09.540
then love can be revolutionary.

00:41:09.540 --> 00:41:11.040
It can change things, right?

00:41:11.040 --> 00:41:14.840
But love is not the
absence of rage.

00:41:14.840 --> 00:41:17.360
Love, the first step
on the path of love

00:41:17.360 --> 00:41:20.102
is actually owning
our moral outrage.

00:41:20.102 --> 00:41:21.560
In the face of the
Executive Orders

00:41:21.560 --> 00:41:23.570
coming down, in the face
of Vincent Chin's murder,

00:41:23.570 --> 00:41:25.236
in the face Balbir
Singh Sodhi's murder,

00:41:25.236 --> 00:41:29.110
in the face of Srinivasjeet's
murder, we ought to be angry.

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:30.659
And we need you to
be angry with us.

00:41:30.659 --> 00:41:31.700
Because here's the thing.

00:41:31.700 --> 00:41:33.800
If we hold our
rage in isolation--

00:41:33.800 --> 00:41:36.100
Hannah Arendt says
isolation breeds tyranny.

00:41:36.100 --> 00:41:38.390
But if we hold our
rage in isolation,

00:41:38.390 --> 00:41:40.820
that's when it
festers into hate.

00:41:40.820 --> 00:41:42.350
That's when it eats us alive.

00:41:42.350 --> 00:41:44.870
And that's when cycles
of aggression continue.

00:41:44.870 --> 00:41:47.720
But if we hold our
rage in community,

00:41:47.720 --> 00:41:50.270
then we can release
its creative energy.

00:41:50.270 --> 00:41:52.250
We walk together on
the path of love.

00:41:52.250 --> 00:41:56.180
And eventually, eventually,
we may arrive in Forgiveness

00:41:56.180 --> 00:41:58.710
because forgiveness
is not forgetting.

00:41:58.710 --> 00:42:01.070
Like I will never forget what
happened to Balbir Uncle,

00:42:01.070 --> 00:42:02.090
never.

00:42:02.090 --> 00:42:04.384
Forgiveness is
freedom from hate.

00:42:04.384 --> 00:42:06.050
That's what Rana Sodhi
taught me when he

00:42:06.050 --> 00:42:07.880
forgave his brother's killer.

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:09.630
But he was free
enough from hate.

00:42:09.630 --> 00:42:12.740
So this Administration
that we're

00:42:12.740 --> 00:42:14.960
fighting, that so many
of us are fighting,

00:42:14.960 --> 00:42:19.320
I refuse to hate them, because
I refuse to be like them.

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:21.290
I will fight them
with my moral outrage

00:42:21.290 --> 00:42:23.120
and with love as
my guiding ethic.

00:42:23.120 --> 00:42:24.890
And eventually, maybe,
it will arrive us

00:42:24.890 --> 00:42:26.510
to a place of forgiveness.

00:42:26.510 --> 00:42:28.940
Because in the end,
our enemies are not

00:42:28.940 --> 00:42:30.260
these individual bad guys.

00:42:30.260 --> 00:42:31.430
It's not Vincent's murderer.

00:42:31.430 --> 00:42:32.280
It's not Frank Roque.

00:42:32.280 --> 00:42:34.154
It's not even this
president or any terrorist

00:42:34.154 --> 00:42:35.600
who tries to attack us.

00:42:35.600 --> 00:42:39.620
Our enemy are the cultures
and the institutions of power

00:42:39.620 --> 00:42:41.134
that allow them to hurt us.

00:42:41.134 --> 00:42:43.300
We can take out as many bad
guys as we want and more

00:42:43.300 --> 00:42:44.780
will step into their place.

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:46.700
But a real, lasting
social change

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:49.130
is changing the context,
changing culture,

00:42:49.130 --> 00:42:50.990
changing institutions of power.

00:42:50.990 --> 00:42:53.420
And so revolutionary love,
the call to revolutionary love

00:42:53.420 --> 00:42:56.300
that we're building right
now in our movement,

00:42:56.300 --> 00:42:59.000
is really taking from
Gandhi and King and Mandela

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.175
and offering a way to
sustain our movement.

00:43:01.175 --> 00:43:03.420
And that's not just in the
next few weeks or months,

00:43:03.420 --> 00:43:05.360
but in the years to come.

00:43:05.360 --> 00:43:08.450
And I think if we walk
with a moral outrage,

00:43:08.450 --> 00:43:12.930
but we're walking on the path
of love, then we'll get there.

00:43:12.930 --> 00:43:19.160
QUYEN DINH: And I think
walking on the path of healing.

00:43:19.160 --> 00:43:23.750
And I think about healing
because we have all

00:43:23.750 --> 00:43:26.720
received those messages,
or as Asian American women.

00:43:26.720 --> 00:43:31.610
I've certainly been told from
my parents to not talk so loud.

00:43:31.610 --> 00:43:37.360
And I have to recognize that
this is how they survived.

00:43:37.360 --> 00:43:41.290
That for them, as
refugees to America

00:43:41.290 --> 00:43:43.210
without a single
word of English,

00:43:43.210 --> 00:43:45.560
this is how they survived.

00:43:45.560 --> 00:43:51.620
And that recognition allows me
to understand that maybe this

00:43:51.620 --> 00:43:53.840
isn't who they want me to be.

00:43:53.840 --> 00:43:54.830
I am someone else.

00:43:54.830 --> 00:43:58.280
In fact, they raised me to be
a very different, strong, loud

00:43:58.280 --> 00:43:59.430
person.

00:43:59.430 --> 00:44:06.670
And by recognizing that, I
release my anger towards them.

00:44:06.670 --> 00:44:12.550
I release my anger towards them
and choose to own my voice.

00:44:12.550 --> 00:44:15.850
I think that on an
individual level,

00:44:15.850 --> 00:44:18.310
it also happened-- this
is on an individual level,

00:44:18.310 --> 00:44:20.590
but it also happens
on a systems level

00:44:20.590 --> 00:44:23.530
in the communities and the
cultures that we create.

00:44:23.530 --> 00:44:26.230
And oftentimes, I
think about reclaiming

00:44:26.230 --> 00:44:28.600
what silence means actually.

00:44:28.600 --> 00:44:33.130
So one of the concepts
that we learn a lot about,

00:44:33.130 --> 00:44:36.670
or that we hear a lot about now
these days, is implicit bias.

00:44:36.670 --> 00:44:39.610
Particularly, against
African-American communities

00:44:39.610 --> 00:44:44.474
being really with huge
assumptions that these are

00:44:44.474 --> 00:44:45.640
communities who are violent.

00:44:45.640 --> 00:44:50.140
And young African-American
boys and girls

00:44:50.140 --> 00:44:54.550
get pushed out of school and
get disciplined at higher rates.

00:44:54.550 --> 00:44:56.140
Whereas Asian
Americans, maybe we

00:44:56.140 --> 00:44:59.740
have benefited from this
because of the assumption

00:44:59.740 --> 00:45:03.580
from educators that you're
the superstar students.

00:45:03.580 --> 00:45:09.200
And oftentimes, I share silence
does not mean understanding.

00:45:09.200 --> 00:45:13.280
Silence can mean that they
are crying out for help

00:45:13.280 --> 00:45:16.070
and they don't know what
to do to get that help.

00:45:16.070 --> 00:45:19.070
And as institutional
leaders, I think

00:45:19.070 --> 00:45:22.790
it is our responsibility
to test those assumptions

00:45:22.790 --> 00:45:26.240
and check our assumptions
and create spaces

00:45:26.240 --> 00:45:29.330
where our voices can be
heard, where our voices lead

00:45:29.330 --> 00:45:32.240
to decisions that
are made beyond just

00:45:32.240 --> 00:45:35.480
our own individual selves,
and the work that we

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:36.837
do 9:00 to 5:00.

00:45:36.837 --> 00:45:38.420
LORRIE MA: And I
think I want to pivot

00:45:38.420 --> 00:45:40.440
that since you kind
of mentioned that you

00:45:40.440 --> 00:45:42.020
