with him that maybe you

01:02:21.800 --> 01:02:28.520
weren't allowed to have,
and just listening to him,

01:02:28.520 --> 01:02:35.030
and recognizing that
you are a part of him.

01:02:35.030 --> 01:02:38.120
And he will continue
your legacy.

01:02:38.120 --> 01:02:41.500
He'll be probably different
from all of us actually.

01:02:41.500 --> 01:02:43.340
But that you have given
him this opportunity

01:02:43.340 --> 01:02:47.330
to define a new identity,
a new self for himself

01:02:47.330 --> 01:02:49.060
and so support that.

01:02:53.970 --> 01:02:56.760
PHIL YU: My daughter is seven
months old, my first child.

01:02:56.760 --> 01:03:00.480
And my question is
same as yours about

01:03:00.480 --> 01:03:01.710
like how will she grow up.

01:03:01.710 --> 01:03:07.620
And I hope that she'd be a
woke ass Asian American woman,

01:03:07.620 --> 01:03:08.540
you know.

01:03:11.300 --> 01:03:13.230
To touch upon something
you said in terms

01:03:13.230 --> 01:03:15.270
of like I don't relate
to this-- and like look.

01:03:15.270 --> 01:03:16.440
I'm Korean American.

01:03:16.440 --> 01:03:19.110
I've gone through relatively
little personal struggle

01:03:19.110 --> 01:03:20.370
in my life.

01:03:20.370 --> 01:03:23.700
But when I said I became
Asian American, that

01:03:23.700 --> 01:03:25.470
means my struggle
became her struggle,

01:03:25.470 --> 01:03:27.120
my struggle became her struggle.

01:03:27.120 --> 01:03:30.450
You know adopting
that mentality really

01:03:30.450 --> 01:03:33.420
is what drives me and
drives the work that I do.

01:03:33.420 --> 01:03:38.090
And so I know a lot of people
will fall back on that thing,

01:03:38.090 --> 01:03:38.970
I can't relate.

01:03:38.970 --> 01:03:40.169
And that's not really--

01:03:40.169 --> 01:03:42.210
I mean, I feel sorry for
you, but I don't relate.

01:03:42.210 --> 01:03:44.585
But at some point-- and I'm
going to paraphrase something

01:03:44.585 --> 01:03:45.950
that someone told me.

01:03:45.950 --> 01:03:49.710
At some point you got to ask
yourself are you interested

01:03:49.710 --> 01:03:52.380
in justice or just us?

01:03:52.380 --> 01:03:55.720
And you have to define
what just us is.

01:03:55.720 --> 01:03:58.800
So when I adopted Asian
American as my identity,

01:03:58.800 --> 01:04:01.449
that's what I took
on, that us part.

01:04:01.449 --> 01:04:02.240
VALARIE KAUR: Yeah.

01:04:02.240 --> 01:04:04.830
Our destinies are intertwined.

01:04:04.830 --> 01:04:07.710
And therefore I can't
give you a single issue.

01:04:10.950 --> 01:04:13.920
Leading with love
means acknowledging

01:04:13.920 --> 01:04:17.450
that everyone's struggle is
intertwined with our own.

01:04:17.450 --> 01:04:19.620
That I cannot live
if you are dying.

01:04:19.620 --> 01:04:22.100
I cannot stand by if
you are suffering.

01:04:22.100 --> 01:04:23.350
What does that mean right now?

01:04:23.350 --> 01:04:24.933
What does it mean
to respond with love

01:04:24.933 --> 01:04:28.920
when so many communities
are in harm's way?

01:04:28.920 --> 01:04:31.110
I mean just even looking
at the first Executive

01:04:31.110 --> 01:04:33.120
Orders the first week
of this Administration,

01:04:33.120 --> 01:04:35.460
we had an Executive
Order that build

01:04:35.460 --> 01:04:39.000
a wall along our southern
border, that punished sanctuary

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:43.140
cities for offering refuge to
undocumented immigrants, that

01:04:43.140 --> 01:04:45.120
started the construction
of pipelines

01:04:45.120 --> 01:04:49.440
on indigenous sacred lands,
that repealed sections

01:04:49.440 --> 01:04:53.000
of the Affordable Care Act,
that now have enacted now

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:55.650
the second version of the
Muslim ban that affects not just

01:04:55.650 --> 01:04:57.750
immigrants and refugees
but Muslims and Sikhs

01:04:57.750 --> 01:04:59.490
and others in this country.

01:04:59.490 --> 01:05:01.230
And now we have promises
of voting rights

01:05:01.230 --> 01:05:04.540
and criminal justice
and mass incarceration.

01:05:04.540 --> 01:05:07.920
But everything will be
affected by this Administration

01:05:07.920 --> 01:05:09.760
and these policies.

01:05:09.760 --> 01:05:13.200
And so, to stand next to my
Latino brothers and sisters,

01:05:13.200 --> 01:05:15.850
and my indigenous brothers and
sisters, and my black brothers

01:05:15.850 --> 01:05:17.850
and sisters, and my Muslim
brothers and sisters,

01:05:17.850 --> 01:05:19.200
and my Asian American brothers--

01:05:19.200 --> 01:05:21.900
I know that sounds exhausting.

01:05:21.900 --> 01:05:24.780
I know what does it look like
each day if all of our issues

01:05:24.780 --> 01:05:28.470
are interconnected and we are
in an intersectional moment?

01:05:28.470 --> 01:05:30.930
And that the only way to fight
for a movement of justice

01:05:30.930 --> 01:05:33.840
now is to know that
we fight together.

01:05:33.840 --> 01:05:37.020
I think that means
deciding how you show up

01:05:37.020 --> 01:05:38.940
in your daily and weekly life.

01:05:38.940 --> 01:05:40.980
So what I'm telling
you is that what

01:05:40.980 --> 01:05:43.980
it means to be an engaged
citizen in America today

01:05:43.980 --> 01:05:46.260
is to call Congress once a day.

01:05:46.260 --> 01:05:47.730
Yes, once a day.

01:05:47.730 --> 01:05:50.990
Like I have the number on
speed dial on my phone.

01:05:50.990 --> 01:05:52.290
I call once a day.

01:05:52.290 --> 01:05:53.330
And I look at the news.

01:05:53.330 --> 01:05:55.663
It's the New York Times," the
same thing you're reading.

01:05:55.663 --> 01:05:57.630
And whatever community
is in harm's way--

01:05:57.630 --> 01:06:00.000
I mean there are so many--
but right now I choose one.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:02.024
And I call my senator
or a representative

01:06:02.024 --> 01:06:04.440
and I tell them I stand in
solidarity with that community,

01:06:04.440 --> 01:06:07.080
stand up, be emboldened
to stand up with me.

01:06:07.080 --> 01:06:08.130
Once a day.

01:06:08.130 --> 01:06:10.320
It means once a week or
once every two weeks,

01:06:10.320 --> 01:06:13.680
showing up to the march,
showing up to the vigil,

01:06:13.680 --> 01:06:16.254
showing up in community not
just online, but in person.

01:06:16.254 --> 01:06:17.670
That's what
solidarity looks like.

01:06:17.670 --> 01:06:19.110
That's what love looks like.

01:06:19.110 --> 01:06:22.200
And if you start to take
your son to these places,

01:06:22.200 --> 01:06:24.420
you don't have to do
very much, because he'll

01:06:24.420 --> 01:06:27.570
be hearing the stories and
having the conversations

01:06:27.570 --> 01:06:29.190
that you didn't get to have.

01:06:29.190 --> 01:06:31.026
And you'll be learning from him.

01:06:31.026 --> 01:06:32.400
Because in order
to love someone,

01:06:32.400 --> 01:06:34.620
you all need to answer
three questions--

01:06:34.620 --> 01:06:36.120
who are you?

01:06:36.120 --> 01:06:38.040
What is at stake for you?

01:06:38.040 --> 01:06:39.550
What is my role in
your flourishing?

01:06:39.550 --> 01:06:40.920
What is your role in mine?

01:06:40.920 --> 01:06:42.300
Number one is who are you?

01:06:42.300 --> 01:06:44.730
Every day I look
into my son's eyes.

01:06:44.730 --> 01:06:47.340
Phil's daughter is
seven months old.

01:06:47.340 --> 01:06:49.660
My son is two years old.

01:06:49.660 --> 01:06:51.300
He is changing every day.

01:06:51.300 --> 01:06:53.880
Every day I have to
ask him who are you?

01:06:53.880 --> 01:06:55.290
What is at stake for you?

01:06:55.290 --> 01:06:56.880
What is my role in
your flourishing

01:06:56.880 --> 01:06:58.131
and what is your role in mine?

01:06:58.131 --> 01:06:59.588
He didn't want me
to get on a plane

01:06:59.588 --> 01:07:01.950
to come over here today and
spend a day away from him.

01:07:01.950 --> 01:07:03.480
But he has a role
in my flourishing

01:07:03.480 --> 01:07:05.970
which is to allow his
mommy to be her best self.

01:07:05.970 --> 01:07:08.649
So we are tied together.

01:07:08.649 --> 01:07:10.440
Not just our communities,
but our families,

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:12.270
and our collective flourishing.

01:07:12.270 --> 01:07:15.450
So if you do that, if you
take your son to these places,

01:07:15.450 --> 01:07:17.130
if you ask him these
questions, if you

01:07:17.130 --> 01:07:18.960
start to create the
culture that you

01:07:18.960 --> 01:07:20.820
want for the country
in your own home,

01:07:20.820 --> 01:07:23.035
then you're part
of the good fight?

01:07:23.035 --> 01:07:24.035
AUDIENCE: Great answers.

01:07:24.035 --> 01:07:25.260
Thank you.

01:07:25.260 --> 01:07:27.300
LORRIE MA: We'll take a
question from the DORY.

01:07:30.190 --> 01:07:32.550
So it says what
work if any have you

01:07:32.550 --> 01:07:34.650
seen in regards to
diversity inclusion

01:07:34.650 --> 01:07:36.390
for Southeast Asian groups?

01:07:36.390 --> 01:07:39.121
Because quote "Asian"
is used so broadly,

01:07:39.121 --> 01:07:41.370
often there is little attention
given to the increased

01:07:41.370 --> 01:07:44.100
representation for more
under-represented groups whose

01:07:44.100 --> 01:07:48.080
experiences can
be very different.

01:07:48.080 --> 01:07:50.810
QUYEN DINH: And is this
in particular to Google?

01:07:53.690 --> 01:07:55.310
LORRIE MA: Feel free
to speak to who.

01:07:55.310 --> 01:07:57.560
QUYEN DINH: Let's start with
Google, since we're here.

01:07:57.560 --> 01:07:59.870
We're having this really
courageous conversation

01:07:59.870 --> 01:08:02.120
about race, right?

01:08:02.120 --> 01:08:04.310
I think the first
step is actually

01:08:04.310 --> 01:08:08.300
recognizing that
there's a problem

01:08:08.300 --> 01:08:11.510
and really owning
that inequity exists

01:08:11.510 --> 01:08:13.910
within the Asian
American community,

01:08:13.910 --> 01:08:17.910
especially around
socioeconomic outcomes.

01:08:17.910 --> 01:08:21.350
And by starting with Google,
one really simple thing

01:08:21.350 --> 01:08:25.760
could be trying to collect this
aggregated data on the Google

01:08:25.760 --> 01:08:26.930
community.

01:08:26.930 --> 01:08:30.851
So of the-- how many Asian
American Google folks

01:08:30.851 --> 01:08:31.350
are there?

01:08:31.350 --> 01:08:32.149
Googlers are there?

01:08:32.149 --> 01:08:33.590
LORRIE MA: I don't know
if we have those numbers.

01:08:33.590 --> 01:08:34.465
PHIL YU: Hello bunch.

01:08:34.465 --> 01:08:35.961
[LAUGHTER]

01:08:35.961 --> 01:08:38.569
QUYEN DINH: Of the hella
bunch Asian American folks,

01:08:38.569 --> 01:08:42.350
or folks who identify as
Asian, how many are Vietnamese?

01:08:42.350 --> 01:08:43.162
How many are Hmong?

01:08:43.162 --> 01:08:44.120
How many are Cambodian?

01:08:44.120 --> 01:08:45.020
How many are Lao?

01:08:45.020 --> 01:08:46.729
How many are Taiwanese?

01:08:46.729 --> 01:08:48.200
How many are Thai?

01:08:48.200 --> 01:08:50.010
How many are Malaysian?

01:08:50.010 --> 01:08:54.160
And I share that because the
Asian American community is not

01:08:54.160 --> 01:08:54.660
the same.

01:08:54.660 --> 01:08:55.970
We're not a monolith.

01:08:55.970 --> 01:09:00.109
And when I try to recruit
for positions at SEARAC

01:09:00.109 --> 01:09:02.479
where we're trying
to pass legislation.

01:09:02.479 --> 01:09:06.470
We're building grassroots
movements and community

01:09:06.470 --> 01:09:09.859
building across the
country, I struggle

01:09:09.859 --> 01:09:13.609
to find folks with a
master's degree or a master's

01:09:13.609 --> 01:09:15.680
in public policy or a
master's in social work

01:09:15.680 --> 01:09:17.120
who are a Southeast Asian.

01:09:17.120 --> 01:09:18.800
Because the reality
is that two in three

01:09:18.800 --> 01:09:22.370
Southeast Asian Americans
don't have a college degree.

01:09:22.370 --> 01:09:26.689
And so you see that manifested
on the professional level

01:09:26.689 --> 01:09:29.060
in different industries where
communities are actually

01:09:29.060 --> 01:09:30.240
represented.

01:09:30.240 --> 01:09:33.800
And I think starting there with
really recognizing that there

01:09:33.800 --> 01:09:35.974
is a problem is the first step.

01:09:39.127 --> 01:09:40.960
LORRIE MA: Let's take
another live question.

01:09:40.960 --> 01:09:41.410
AUDIENCE: Great.

01:09:41.410 --> 01:09:42.910
Thank you everyone
for coming today.

01:09:42.910 --> 01:09:45.220
So I have a question more
about personal identity.

01:09:45.220 --> 01:09:47.854
I was born in the US,
but I grew up in Taiwan,

01:09:47.854 --> 01:09:49.270
but I'm at a
bilingual school that

01:09:49.270 --> 01:09:52.430
taught both American
and Chinese history.

01:09:52.430 --> 01:09:55.210
And I had most of my career
in the United States.

01:09:55.210 --> 01:09:57.647
So I don't really
know what I am.

01:09:57.647 --> 01:09:59.230
I don't feel like I
belong in America.

01:09:59.230 --> 01:10:03.070
I don't feel like I belong when
I go back to Taiwan or in Asia.

01:10:03.070 --> 01:10:05.170
And so I've always called
myself Asian American.

01:10:05.170 --> 01:10:07.799
But I don't really feel like
I'm the same as everyone

01:10:07.799 --> 01:10:08.840
else in this room either.

01:10:08.840 --> 01:10:11.050
So I'm just curious from
your personal experience,

01:10:11.050 --> 01:10:14.380
you know, where do you
fit in and how do you

01:10:14.380 --> 01:10:17.090
find that belonging?

01:10:17.090 --> 01:10:20.690
VALARIE KAUR: I just want
to say, I know you're heart.

01:10:20.690 --> 01:10:22.370
So growing up as
a third generation

01:10:22.370 --> 01:10:25.359
Sikh American in the farmlands
of central California--

01:10:25.359 --> 01:10:26.400
what does that look like?

01:10:26.400 --> 01:10:29.690
It means that when I would go
to the gurdwara, the Sikh house

01:10:29.690 --> 01:10:32.300
of worship, there were
mostly immigrant families.

01:10:32.300 --> 01:10:35.780
And I felt like an outsider
to my own Sikh community

01:10:35.780 --> 01:10:38.150
because my father was
born and raised here.

01:10:38.150 --> 01:10:40.340
He went to college
and was part of a frat

01:10:40.340 --> 01:10:44.030
and he named me Valarie
after Valentine's Day,

01:10:44.030 --> 01:10:46.680
not after like anything
I tried to pretend--

01:10:46.680 --> 01:10:47.180
No.

01:10:47.180 --> 01:10:47.680
No.

01:10:47.680 --> 01:10:49.700
But it's after an
American holiday,

01:10:49.700 --> 01:10:51.080
it's not in Sikh scripture.

01:10:51.080 --> 01:10:51.775
So I--

01:10:51.775 --> 01:10:54.080
[LAUGHTER]

01:10:54.080 --> 01:10:56.870
So I felt like an outsider
to my own community.

01:10:56.870 --> 01:11:00.110
And then at school, of
course, predominantly white,

01:11:00.110 --> 01:11:02.140
very conservative,
very Christian,

01:11:02.140 --> 01:11:04.180
I was constantly
called these names,

01:11:04.180 --> 01:11:06.620
but also told that I would
go to hell because I was not

01:11:06.620 --> 01:11:07.160
Christian.

01:11:07.160 --> 01:11:10.460
And so I spent my
entire childhood

01:11:10.460 --> 01:11:14.060
feeling like I was in between,
like I am not fully Sikh

01:11:14.060 --> 01:11:15.170
according to them.

01:11:15.170 --> 01:11:17.960
I'm not fully American
according to them.

01:11:17.960 --> 01:11:20.720
And this in-between
space I felt like I just

01:11:20.720 --> 01:11:22.160
wanted to collapse it.

01:11:22.160 --> 01:11:24.410
I thought about changing my
name to go this direction.

01:11:24.410 --> 01:11:26.100
And I thought about
doing something else

01:11:26.100 --> 01:11:27.300
to go in this direction.

01:11:27.300 --> 01:11:31.730
And finally, it was only
after, really after 9/11,

01:11:31.730 --> 01:11:34.880
and understanding
what I was seeing

01:11:34.880 --> 01:11:38.630
that I recognized this
in-between space that I

01:11:38.630 --> 01:11:39.740
occupied.

01:11:39.740 --> 01:11:42.400
This in-between space
that you're standing in

01:11:42.400 --> 01:11:45.300
is actually a space of
tremendous strength.

01:11:45.300 --> 01:11:48.840
You can see things that
other people can't see.

01:11:48.840 --> 01:11:52.020
You can see things about America
and Taiwan and China that

01:11:52.020 --> 01:11:54.000
others of us in this
room cannot see.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:11:56.010
I can see things that
others cannot see.

01:11:56.010 --> 01:11:59.220
And that means I can tell
stories from this space that

01:11:59.220 --> 01:12:00.750
others cannot tell.

01:12:00.750 --> 01:12:03.570
I can exercise my
voice from this space.

01:12:03.570 --> 01:12:06.030
My best friend tells me speak
even if your voice trembles.

01:12:06.030 --> 01:12:08.940
So even if your voice
is trembling, speak.

01:12:08.940 --> 01:12:11.760
Because your particular
truth is something

01:12:11.760 --> 01:12:15.150
that this country, this
community here on this campus,

01:12:15.150 --> 01:12:16.020
needs.

01:12:16.020 --> 01:12:17.430
We need you.

01:12:17.430 --> 01:12:19.800
So own where you are.

01:12:19.800 --> 01:12:21.900
And also know that
you're not alone

01:12:21.900 --> 01:12:23.940
in where you are,
that so many of us

01:12:23.940 --> 01:12:25.710
are occupying these
in-between spaces.

01:12:25.710 --> 01:12:27.210
A whole generation
of millennials

01:12:27.210 --> 01:12:29.410
are in these in-between spaces.

01:12:29.410 --> 01:12:32.160
And one of the fallacies of
races to put us in these cages,

01:12:32.160 --> 01:12:32.660
right?

01:12:32.660 --> 01:12:34.620
We can break open those cages.

01:12:34.620 --> 01:12:39.000
We can show that America is not
a melting pot, it's a mosaic.

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:40.650
And it's made up of
all different kinds

01:12:40.650 --> 01:12:43.470
of pieces and histories
and stories and truths.

01:12:43.470 --> 01:12:45.630
And your job is to
let your truth shine.

01:12:45.630 --> 01:12:49.760
Your job is to let
your truth sing.

01:12:49.760 --> 01:12:50.700
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:12:50.700 --> 01:12:52.640
PHIL YU: I just
want to add to that.

01:12:52.640 --> 01:12:56.060
There is no corner of
Asian America where

01:12:56.060 --> 01:12:59.885
this diverse, incredible, wide
spanning Asian America, where

01:12:59.885 --> 01:13:02.260
somebody's going to go and
feel like I completely belong,

01:13:02.260 --> 01:13:05.480
like I totally belong here.

01:13:05.480 --> 01:13:06.920
There's a corner
everywhere where

01:13:06.920 --> 01:13:09.320
someone is going to like I
don't feel like I belong.

01:13:09.320 --> 01:13:12.530
And that's kind of
what's awesome about it.

01:13:12.530 --> 01:13:15.799
But I think everyone has
felt like an outsider

01:13:15.799 --> 01:13:17.840
in some space of the space
where they're supposed

01:13:17.840 --> 01:13:19.830
to feel like they belong.

01:13:19.830 --> 01:13:23.240
I think we can all
relate on some level.

01:13:23.240 --> 01:13:24.761
And then ditto
what Valarie said.

01:13:24.761 --> 01:13:28.392
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:28.392 --> 01:13:29.100
LORRIE MA: Great.

