here in this room
raising their hand when

01:13:41.810 --> 01:13:44.150
I talk to people who
are not from California,

01:13:44.150 --> 01:13:47.330
they don't even know about
the Japanese internment.

01:13:47.330 --> 01:13:51.110
What are some of the larger
effort going across the country

01:13:51.110 --> 01:13:54.260
to educate the world at
large, and America at large,

01:13:54.260 --> 01:13:57.520
about the injustice
against Asian Americans

01:13:57.520 --> 01:13:58.586
and the world in general?

01:14:01.270 --> 01:14:03.020
PHIL YU: I don't know
specifically to much

01:14:03.020 --> 01:14:04.880
about education
issues, but I can only

01:14:04.880 --> 01:14:06.380
say from what I
know from people who

01:14:06.380 --> 01:14:09.000
are on the ground doing
some work is that it happens

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:09.950
on a local level.

01:14:09.950 --> 01:14:13.850
I mean a lot of it
is super motivated

01:14:13.850 --> 01:14:17.420
by people within schools,
within school districts,

01:14:17.420 --> 01:14:18.770
to educate about--

01:14:18.770 --> 01:14:21.727
in California, we have
Fred Korematsu Day.

01:14:21.727 --> 01:14:23.060
That's not a nationwide holiday.

01:14:23.060 --> 01:14:25.100
But it's celebrating
a civil rights

01:14:25.100 --> 01:14:27.235
leader who stood up
to the incarceration

01:14:27.235 --> 01:14:30.272
of Japanese Americans.

01:14:30.272 --> 01:14:33.750
I have a friend of
mine, this couple,

01:14:33.750 --> 01:14:37.340
they have two kids 10 and 11
years old at their school.

01:14:37.340 --> 01:14:39.920
Their school was
celebrating Dr. Seuss week

01:14:39.920 --> 01:14:45.629
in conjunction with National
Book something week, reading

01:14:45.629 --> 01:14:46.670
week, or something right?

01:14:46.670 --> 01:14:49.024
And they're
celebrating Dr. Seuss.

01:14:49.024 --> 01:14:49.940
People love Dr. Seuss.

01:14:49.940 --> 01:14:52.190
But a lot of people don't
know that Dr. Seuss actually

01:14:52.190 --> 01:14:55.460
has a history of making really
racist cartoons during World

01:14:55.460 --> 01:14:57.950
War II against
Japanese Americans,

01:14:57.950 --> 01:15:01.520
painting them as the enemy
in super racist caricature.

01:15:01.520 --> 01:15:03.500
So my friends, their
kids, 10, and 11,

01:15:03.500 --> 01:15:05.570
took it upon themselves--
these are some woke ass

01:15:05.570 --> 01:15:09.050
kids-- they took it upon
themselves to create flyers.

01:15:09.050 --> 01:15:10.970
They designed themselves,
they printed up.

01:15:10.970 --> 01:15:12.928
And they passed it out
at school to their class

01:15:12.928 --> 01:15:15.920
and would say did you know
that Dr. Seuss is racist?

01:15:15.920 --> 01:15:18.320
Did you know that he made
these racist cartoons?

01:15:18.320 --> 01:15:23.400
They got it confiscated by the
teachers and a note home saying

01:15:23.400 --> 01:15:28.280
dear, Mr Wong, while
we appreciate your kids

01:15:28.280 --> 01:15:31.970
taking the initiative
to be socially aware,

01:15:31.970 --> 01:15:34.237
these not allowed.

01:15:34.237 --> 01:15:35.570
But I was like, that is amazing.

01:15:35.570 --> 01:15:41.300
But it took these kids to
provide an alternate point

01:15:41.300 --> 01:15:43.970
of view than just
go along with sort

01:15:43.970 --> 01:15:47.860
of the celebration of this
figure, who most people love

01:15:47.860 --> 01:15:49.460
the work that they know about.

01:15:49.460 --> 01:15:54.085
But I think stuff
like that, that's

01:15:54.085 --> 01:15:55.710
just a really cute
example of something

01:15:55.710 --> 01:15:58.670
that-- but I feel like it takes
efforts like that where people

01:15:58.670 --> 01:16:02.210
start a different
conversation entirely

01:16:02.210 --> 01:16:05.450
where you have to create this
alternate thing than what's

01:16:05.450 --> 01:16:06.690
been ingrained.

01:16:06.690 --> 01:16:08.720
Like I said, I got
super mad about learning

01:16:08.720 --> 01:16:11.246
about Vincent Chin in Ethics
Studies course in college.

01:16:11.246 --> 01:16:14.330
It took getting to college
and definitely not everybody

01:16:14.330 --> 01:16:16.650
gets to take Ethnic
Studies courses.

01:16:16.650 --> 01:16:19.520
And so personally,
if it were up to me,

01:16:19.520 --> 01:16:22.080
I would push for ethnic
studies at the high school,

01:16:22.080 --> 01:16:25.445
junior high level, honestly.

01:16:25.445 --> 01:16:28.330
VALARIE KAUR: So my most
recent social justice issue

01:16:28.330 --> 01:16:29.970
was net neutrality.

01:16:29.970 --> 01:16:33.240
And there were fellow
advocates who'd

01:16:33.240 --> 01:16:35.010
been with me for
many years working

01:16:35.010 --> 01:16:36.600
on hate crimes,
mass incarceration,

01:16:36.600 --> 01:16:38.910
solitary confinement,
immigration, thinking

01:16:38.910 --> 01:16:42.900
what are you doing taking on
the issue of internet freedom

01:16:42.900 --> 01:16:44.070
as a social justice issue?

01:16:44.070 --> 01:16:46.050
I was working here
at Stanford Law.

01:16:46.050 --> 01:16:48.780
And I want to say I felt
so proud of the stand

01:16:48.780 --> 01:16:50.790
Google took on this issue.

01:16:50.790 --> 01:16:53.670
Because I chose net neutrality
as a social justice issue

01:16:53.670 --> 01:16:55.650
because my life as
an activist would not

01:16:55.650 --> 01:16:56.861
be possible without it.

01:16:56.861 --> 01:16:57.360
PHIL YU: No.

01:16:57.360 --> 01:17:00.030
VALARIE KAUR: I had no way
to tell, to show my film,

01:17:00.030 --> 01:17:02.040
if it weren't for the
open and free internet.

01:17:02.040 --> 01:17:04.710
Activists like us, you
wouldn't have a blog,

01:17:04.710 --> 01:17:06.390
we wouldn't have
our calls to action.

01:17:06.390 --> 01:17:08.460
There's a whole generation
of activists now

01:17:08.460 --> 01:17:11.370
who are telling the stories of
Vincent Chin and Balbir Singh

01:17:11.370 --> 01:17:14.130
Sodhi and Srinivas
Kuchibhotla, because

01:17:14.130 --> 01:17:15.990
of the open and free internet.

01:17:15.990 --> 01:17:17.970
And so there are
resources available to you

01:17:17.970 --> 01:17:20.170
now in ways that
they weren't before.

01:17:20.170 --> 01:17:23.250
And the first film that
we made, "Divided We

01:17:23.250 --> 01:17:25.770
Fall" about hate
crimes after 9/11

01:17:25.770 --> 01:17:28.980
also includes history
honoring the Japanese American

01:17:28.980 --> 01:17:30.330
internment.

01:17:30.330 --> 01:17:32.670
And so that film has
been used in classrooms

01:17:32.670 --> 01:17:33.930
all around the country.

01:17:33.930 --> 01:17:35.710
We've made it
available for free.

01:17:35.710 --> 01:17:38.760
So many resources out
there for you online.

01:17:38.760 --> 01:17:41.190
But if you go to
revolutionarylove.net

01:17:41.190 --> 01:17:43.530
you can find this film and
a whole lot of other calls

01:17:43.530 --> 01:17:48.940
to action to help you tell the
stories that need to be told.

01:17:48.940 --> 01:17:51.360
LORRIE MA: We have this
question from the DORY.

01:17:51.360 --> 01:17:54.840
Asian American are the largest
minority group at Google.

01:17:54.840 --> 01:17:57.270
How can we get this group
more involved in the issues

01:17:57.270 --> 01:17:59.460
surrounding more
underrepresented minorities

01:17:59.460 --> 01:18:00.840
at Google?

01:18:00.840 --> 01:18:03.120
On the other side of the
coin, what are the issues

01:18:03.120 --> 01:18:05.010
that Asian American
Googlers needs support

01:18:05.010 --> 01:18:07.322
from from other
underrepresented groups?

01:18:16.470 --> 01:18:18.050
QUYEN DINH: So this is an--

01:18:18.050 --> 01:18:18.550
go ahead.

01:18:18.550 --> 01:18:19.050
PHIL YU: No.

01:18:19.050 --> 01:18:19.550
Ah.

01:18:19.550 --> 01:18:22.050
[LAUGHTER]

01:18:24.972 --> 01:18:28.970
On the question of how do we get
other Asian American involved?

01:18:28.970 --> 01:18:32.150
Like that's the question that
is asked of me by every student

01:18:32.150 --> 01:18:32.975
group on every--

01:18:32.975 --> 01:18:34.850
Asian American student
group on every campus.

01:18:34.850 --> 01:18:37.070
How do I get the Asian
American on this campus

01:18:37.070 --> 01:18:39.560
to give a shit about what
we give a shit about?

01:18:39.560 --> 01:18:43.050
It's like the problem is that
you can't get someone else,

01:18:43.050 --> 01:18:46.340
you can't care on their behalf,
like you've got to get them--

01:18:46.340 --> 01:18:49.940
they have to come around
to being the ones who move.

01:18:49.940 --> 01:18:53.212
So you can do all that
mobilizing you want,

01:18:53.212 --> 01:18:54.920
at some point it has
to be the initiative

01:18:54.920 --> 01:18:56.390
from within the individual.

01:18:56.390 --> 01:19:00.080
There's no secret
link that's going

01:19:00.080 --> 01:19:04.290
to trick somebody into caring.

01:19:04.290 --> 01:19:06.057
So I don't know.

01:19:06.057 --> 01:19:07.640
I don't know what
it takes in terms of

01:19:07.640 --> 01:19:10.250
like how do I get
people to care?

01:19:10.250 --> 01:19:12.639
Like they have to care.

01:19:12.639 --> 01:19:14.430
I don't know what magic
key there is to it.

01:19:17.040 --> 01:19:17.540
OK.

01:19:17.540 --> 01:19:18.837
Yeah.

01:19:18.837 --> 01:19:20.420
VALARIE KAUR: Well
I was just thinking

01:19:20.420 --> 01:19:22.003
about how you are
like you have to opt

01:19:22.003 --> 01:19:23.900
into Asian American
identity, right?

01:19:23.900 --> 01:19:26.360
And if your definition
of Asian American

01:19:26.360 --> 01:19:30.560
includes me, that means
when I'm at the vigil

01:19:30.560 --> 01:19:33.264
and I'm burying my people,
cremating my people,

01:19:33.264 --> 01:19:35.180
you're going to be right
there with me, right?

01:19:35.180 --> 01:19:39.410
Because you see me as
part of who you are.

01:19:39.410 --> 01:19:43.940
And the way to do that, the way
to see one another as brothers

01:19:43.940 --> 01:19:48.810
and sisters so that we
care is through stories.

01:19:48.810 --> 01:19:51.415
That is the only magic
key I found in my 15 years

01:19:51.415 --> 01:19:52.040
as an activist.

01:19:52.040 --> 01:19:54.710
It was never the lawsuit or
the Op Ed or the sound bite.

01:19:54.710 --> 01:19:57.590
It was always
telling a story that

01:19:57.590 --> 01:20:03.600
made people see what it
is like through our eyes,

01:20:03.600 --> 01:20:05.490
feel what we feel.

01:20:05.490 --> 01:20:08.640
I saw so many of you wipe
away tears when some of us

01:20:08.640 --> 01:20:10.440
were telling these stories.

01:20:10.440 --> 01:20:14.680
If you feel what we feel that
stories can cultivate empathy,

01:20:14.680 --> 01:20:16.680
and stories can cultivate
that kind of empathy

01:20:16.680 --> 01:20:21.180
required to inspire
action, collective action.

01:20:21.180 --> 01:20:23.730
I don't think we get Asian
Americans to stand up out

01:20:23.730 --> 01:20:26.160
of a sense of duty
or obligation.

01:20:26.160 --> 01:20:28.302
Love is not an
exchange economy, I'll

01:20:28.302 --> 01:20:29.760
do it for you so
that you'll do it.

01:20:29.760 --> 01:20:32.610
No, it's like the
call to love is

01:20:32.610 --> 01:20:34.329
to ask one another who are you?

01:20:34.329 --> 01:20:36.120
And the best way to
ask one another who are

01:20:36.120 --> 01:20:39.426
is to hear each other's stories,
to be moved by one another,

01:20:39.426 --> 01:20:41.800
and then show up for one
another when we need each other.

01:20:41.800 --> 01:20:45.480
So the fact that we're
having forums like this where

01:20:45.480 --> 01:20:48.930
a lot of this is testimony
asking you to be with us

01:20:48.930 --> 01:20:52.350
and hearing you so that we
can be with you through films,

01:20:52.350 --> 01:20:55.830
through roundtables, online,
on the ground, in person.

01:20:55.830 --> 01:20:57.930
The more that the
companies like Google

01:20:57.930 --> 01:21:00.240
invest in that
kind of work, then

01:21:00.240 --> 01:21:04.030
we won't be pulling teeth
to get people to show up,

01:21:04.030 --> 01:21:05.112
we'll just be showing up.

01:21:05.112 --> 01:21:05.820
QUYEN DINH: Yeah.

01:21:05.820 --> 01:21:08.290
I was going to say, this
is a Google question.

01:21:08.290 --> 01:21:10.800
This is a Google conversation.

01:21:10.800 --> 01:21:14.145
I can't pretend to know
what happens on this campus.

01:21:14.145 --> 01:21:16.500
I am in a totally different
world, where I'm like,

01:21:16.500 --> 01:21:19.270
OK, I don't know why my
Google Drive file was

01:21:19.270 --> 01:21:20.740
like duplicating,
but like that's

01:21:20.740 --> 01:21:23.680
like the extent my relationship.

01:21:23.680 --> 01:21:28.300
You all-- and the way that
I think about advocacy

01:21:28.300 --> 01:21:30.490
is really about
owning your story

01:21:30.490 --> 01:21:34.810
and really starting there,
And having not this discussion

01:21:34.810 --> 01:21:37.060
with us as panelists, but
having a discussion with you

01:21:37.060 --> 01:21:41.560
all as a community to understand
who you are, what you care

01:21:41.560 --> 01:21:44.590
about, what are the challenges
that you experience,

01:21:44.590 --> 01:21:47.830
and also what are the challenges
that other people of color

01:21:47.830 --> 01:21:49.510
experience at Google.

01:21:49.510 --> 01:21:54.830
Where is their common
passion and love?

01:21:54.830 --> 01:21:58.510
And it's not going to happen
with one conversation or two

01:21:58.510 --> 01:21:59.650
or three.

01:21:59.650 --> 01:22:01.020
But it will.

01:22:01.020 --> 01:22:03.550
It will happen if there
is that commitment

01:22:03.550 --> 01:22:08.000
to really understanding
who we are as a community.

01:22:08.000 --> 01:22:11.332
LORRIE MA: Great We have
two more live questions.

01:22:14.224 --> 01:22:17.360
AUDIENCE: I think I'm
going to break this.

01:22:17.360 --> 01:22:18.820
I have so many
things on my mind,

01:22:18.820 --> 01:22:22.220
I'll try to pose my question
as clearly as I can.

01:22:22.220 --> 01:22:23.900
So during the
election, I happened

01:22:23.900 --> 01:22:26.270
to meet a couple of
people like Uber drivers

01:22:26.270 --> 01:22:28.370
and they were Trump supporters.

01:22:28.370 --> 01:22:31.640
And I asked them why had
they voted for Trump.

01:22:31.640 --> 01:22:33.200
The answer was very common.

01:22:33.200 --> 01:22:35.866
And there was one thing that was
very common and similar to what

01:22:35.866 --> 01:22:39.350
Phil had mentioned that
immigrants had taken jobs

01:22:39.350 --> 01:22:39.900
from them.

01:22:42.450 --> 01:22:46.680
My personal opinion, I pay
shitloads of taxes every year,

01:22:46.680 --> 01:22:49.650
but I just didn't have
the facts to explain

01:22:49.650 --> 01:22:51.090
to them that this is not true.

01:22:51.090 --> 01:22:54.210
And this was a question for me
as well, is this actually true?

01:22:54.210 --> 01:22:57.000
If she's a mother of two
and she doesn't have money

01:22:57.000 --> 01:22:57.840
to feed her kids.

01:22:57.840 --> 01:23:00.090
And somebody who
has the authority

01:23:00.090 --> 01:23:02.580
is feeding to her that
all immigrants have

01:23:02.580 --> 01:23:05.640
taken over the job and that's
why you don't have money.

01:23:05.640 --> 01:23:07.960
I wonder these kind
of forums are good,

01:23:07.960 --> 01:23:09.930
but is there any
platform for people

01:23:09.930 --> 01:23:12.690
who actually think that
that is the reason that they

01:23:12.690 --> 01:23:14.790
don't have jobs
because immigrants

01:23:14.790 --> 01:23:15.870
have taken over the jobs?

01:23:15.870 --> 01:23:17.310
Have you ever spoken to anybody?

01:23:17.310 --> 01:23:19.880
I tried to look online, but
I couldn't find any fact

01:23:19.880 --> 01:23:22.242
where they could
explain that whatever

01:23:22.242 --> 01:23:23.700
tax money that
immigrants would pay

01:23:23.700 --> 01:23:26.520
would also go towards
the economy of America

01:23:26.520 --> 01:23:28.740
and not their own country.

01:23:28.740 --> 01:23:32.370
And I wondered if you have
anything online or any forums

01:23:32.370 --> 01:23:36.360
or any discussions to
people who actually think

01:23:36.360 --> 01:23:39.272
that that's the reason
why they are out of jobs

01:23:39.272 --> 01:23:41.228
or why there are
against immigrants?

01:23:47.970 --> 01:23:50.350
QUYEN DINH: Data
can be manipulated.

01:23:50.350 --> 01:23:53.380
So there's data from very
conservative think tanks saying

01:23:53.380 --> 01:23:55.900
that immigrants are
taking our jobs.

01:23:55.900 --> 01:23:58.120
There's also very
substantial data

01:23:58.120 --> 01:24:00.160
that says that is not the case.

01:24:00.160 --> 01:24:04.570
And I would take a
step back actually

01:24:04.570 --> 01:24:06.330
in thinking about this
Uber conversation.

01:24:06.330 --> 01:24:08.800
I would ask why
do you think that?

01:24:08.800 --> 01:24:11.620
Is this something that
you have experienced?

01:24:11.620 --> 01:24:14.260
Or is it something that
you've heard on the news?

01:24:14.260 --> 01:24:16.270
Because very often
times, I think

01:24:16.270 --> 01:24:20.830
it's hearing things on the news
through outlets that manipulate

01:24:20.830 --> 01:24:25.930
information and frame what is at
crisis in a very different way.

01:24:25.930 --> 01:24:27.760
Because I think
what is at crisis

01:24:27.760 --> 01:24:32.790
is that low income
communities need more jobs

01:24:32.790 --> 01:24:35.070
and that we as a
country have not

01:24:35.070 --> 01:24:39.420
been able to grow enough
infrastructure here

01:24:39.420 --> 01:24:43.710
for all Americans of all
socioeconomic ladders

01:24:43.710 --> 01:24:45.580
to have access to those jobs.

01:24:45.580 --> 01:24:48.240
So those coal miners
in Pennsylvania,

01:24:48.240 --> 01:24:50.820
is Donald Trump bringing
back the coal industry?

01:24:50.820 --> 01:24:53.820
I don't know how he's
going to do that.

01:24:53.820 --> 01:24:57.180
But that conversation is not
one, that honest conversation,

01:24:57.180 --> 01:24:58.980
is not one that's being had.

01:24:58.980 --> 01:25:01.740
And my interpretation
is, therefore,

01:25:01.740 --> 01:25:05.220
that they're manipulating
fears of Americans who

01:25:05.220 --> 01:25:08.280
want to make a living, who
want to make an honest earning,

01:25:08.280 --> 01:25:11.490
and be able to keep
their families together.

01:25:11.490 --> 01:25:14.010
And they are manipulating
that sense of fear

01:25:14.010 --> 01:25:15.870
and that sense of
scarcity instead

01:25:15.870 --> 01:25:17.784
of focusing on the
real question at hand,

01:25:17.784 --> 01:25:19.950
which is how are we going
to create new jobs for all

01:25:19.950 --> 01:25:20.850
of America?

01:25:20.850 --> 01:25:22.140
How are you going to do that?

01:25:22.140 --> 01:25:24.780
Show me through your policies,
not through your rhetoric,

01:25:24.780 --> 01:25:26.700
show me through your
policies how you're

01:25:26.700 --> 01:25:29.335
going to create this America?

01:25:29.335 --> 01:25:31.460
PHIL YU: You're also
operating under the assumption

01:25:31.460 --> 01:25:35.180
that a conversation like
that in the Uber car

01:25:35.180 --> 01:25:36.830
or whatever that
the person is going

01:25:36.830 --> 01:25:41.709
to be persuaded or dissuaded
by facts, by actual facts, when

01:25:41.709 --> 01:25:44.000
I know that a lot of the
times we're in that situation,

01:25:44.000 --> 01:25:46.340
it's like the person has
already made up their mind.

01:25:46.340 --> 01:25:50.215
They're not interested in
being persuaded with numbers.

01:25:53.000 --> 01:25:56.390
That's where you have to have
a more personal conversation

01:25:56.390 --> 01:25:59.890
than just I'm more
right than you.

01:25:59.890 --> 01:26:01.890
There's something more
to it than that you know.

01:26:01.890 --> 01:26:02.285
LORRIE MA: Great.

01:26:02.285 --> 01:26:02.810
Yeah.

01:26:02.810 --> 01:26:07.160
We have time for
one last question.

01:26:07.160 --> 01:26:08.930
AUDIENCE: So speaking
of people who

01:26:08.930 --> 01:26:11.810
have made up their mind
already about a lot of things,

01:26:11.810 --> 01:26:17.210
my parents immigrated here from
the Philippines 35 years ago.

01:26:17.210 --> 01:26:21.800
They are your prototypical
survivors here in the US.

01:26:21.800 --> 01:26:23.480
Made their way here.

01:26:23.480 --> 01:26:28.280
Raised me and my two
brothers to also be survivors

01:26:28.280 --> 01:26:32.300
and to excel and to kind of
make our way without kind

01:26:32.300 --> 01:26:35.720
of ruffling too many feathers.

01:26:35.720 --> 01:26:37.910
And it was only
after I came out here

01:26:37.910 --> 01:26:40.040
to California going
to college out here

01:26:40.040 --> 01:26:42.150
that I kind of
had my mind opened

01:26:42.150 --> 01:26:44.600
and to be exposed to what
being Asian American meant,

01:26:44.600 --> 01:26:49.880
and just kind of being accepting
of other cultures as well.

01:26:49.880 --> 01:26:52.520
But where I struggle is kind
of in having that conversation

01:26:52.520 --> 01:26:54.019
back with my parents,
with the older

01:26:54.019 --> 01:26:56.196
generation, the survivors.

01:26:56.196 --> 01:26:58.070
They have they seem to
have a little bit more

01:26:58.070 --> 01:27:01.340
of a mental block about these
issues because of the situation

01:27:01.340 --> 01:27:04.004
that they went through
many years ago.

01:27:04.004 --> 01:27:05.420
So do you have any
advice for kind

01:27:05.420 --> 01:27:09.010
of how to approach conversations
with the older generations?

01:27:09.010 --> 01:27:12.890
Because I think our age group
are more socially accepting.

01:27:12.890 --> 01:27:14.690
We are talking
about these issues,

01:27:14.690 --> 01:27:17.606
whereas my parents and
that generation are not.

01:27:25.100 --> 01:27:27.375
PHIL YU: For me, that's
another argument--

01:27:27.375 --> 01:27:29.750
it's not an argument, but
another conversation that's not

01:27:29.750 --> 01:27:30.700
going to be--

01:27:30.700 --> 01:27:32.630
no one's going to be
persuaded by being

01:27:32.630 --> 01:27:34.880
like I'm more right than
you, especially when you're

01:27:34.880 --> 01:27:37.087
dealing with your own parents.

01:27:37.087 --> 01:27:38.670
That needs to be
approached with love.

01:27:38.670 --> 01:27:43.560
And I think a lot of that
comes from sort of exhibiting

01:27:43.560 --> 01:27:47.754
and showing the way you live,
the relationship you have,

01:27:47.754 --> 01:27:49.670
the relationships that
you have and the things

01:27:49.670 --> 01:27:51.620
that you stand for.

01:27:51.620 --> 01:27:53.300
And then not just
like those crazy kids,

01:27:53.300 --> 01:27:56.170
but it's like this is I'm very
passionate about these things.

01:27:56.170 --> 01:27:58.610
I'm passionate about-- I
don't know what particularly

01:27:58.610 --> 01:28:01.340
what kind of attitudes
you're speaking to,

01:28:01.340 --> 01:28:06.050
but it does take sometimes
even the stodgiest, most

01:28:06.050 --> 01:28:09.200
like ingrained kind
of thinking can

01:28:09.200 --> 01:28:12.230
be persuaded by
people who live out

01:28:12.230 --> 01:28:16.160
and model a certain way of life,
even from those crazy kids.

01:28:16.160 --> 01:28:18.620
So I do think it
is something that

01:28:18.620 --> 01:28:23.120
needs to be approached
from showing an experience

01:28:23.120 --> 01:28:25.870
rather than being like
you're wrong mom or dad.

01:28:25.870 --> 01:28:26.870
You're out of your mind.

01:28:30.710 --> 01:28:36.800
That's me talking as a kid
and having those conversations

01:28:36.800 --> 01:28:39.640
where you're going to
run into some blocks.

01:28:42.500 --> 01:28:48.120
But I also think that it's OK
to take a breather from that

01:28:48.120 --> 01:28:49.862
and be like not so
frustrated, because I

01:28:49.862 --> 01:28:51.570
know a lot people who
are like my parents

01:28:51.570 --> 01:28:53.880
are driving me crazy.

01:28:53.880 --> 01:28:57.440
But it's also OK
to keep on trying

01:28:57.440 --> 01:28:59.040
it's a long game sometimes.

01:29:02.824 --> 01:29:05.160
QUYEN DINH: I was just going
to say that my dad still

01:29:05.160 --> 01:29:06.570
doesn't know what I do really.

01:29:06.570 --> 01:29:08.402
[LAUGHTER]

01:29:11.592 --> 01:29:13.550
If I were to tell him
I'm an engineer, ah yeah,

01:29:13.550 --> 01:29:15.230
it's awesome.

01:29:15.230 --> 01:29:16.740
Executive director, hmm.

01:29:16.740 --> 01:29:17.240
Policy?

01:29:17.240 --> 01:29:18.680
Hmm, weird.

01:29:22.080 --> 01:29:28.830
He is the apolitical
Republican actually,

01:29:28.830 --> 01:29:32.610
Republican by history
and experience

01:29:32.610 --> 01:29:34.890
as opposed to policy.

01:29:34.890 --> 01:29:37.600
And in my--

01:29:37.600 --> 01:29:40.680
I don't know-- like 15
years ish of work now,

01:29:40.680 --> 01:29:45.990
it's been really
moving to just have

01:29:45.990 --> 01:29:48.480
conversations with
him about why he

01:29:48.480 --> 01:29:50.550
thinks the way that he thinks.

01:29:50.550 --> 01:29:56.700
And moments of random
education kind of open up,

01:29:56.700 --> 01:30:00.690
and that's when I share with him
a little bit about the policy

01:30:00.690 --> 01:30:01.950
work that we do.

01:30:01.950 --> 01:30:04.260
And I do try to
make it personal.

01:30:04.260 --> 01:30:07.090
So when we talk about
deportation, for example,

01:30:07.090 --> 01:30:10.410
it's not an issue that folks
think that Asian American are

01:30:10.410 --> 01:30:11.880
impacted by.

01:30:11.880 --> 01:30:14.550
And for the Southeast
Asian American experience,

01:30:14.550 --> 01:30:16.500
it's even less known.

01:30:16.500 --> 01:30:19.890
And I shared with him, you know
when you think of my cousin--

01:30:19.890 --> 01:30:23.930
who my dad sponsored over
as like a 14-year-old--

01:30:23.930 --> 01:30:25.830
I said, do you remember
what his experience

01:30:25.830 --> 01:30:30.610
was like growing up without
parents really here in the US?

01:30:30.610 --> 01:30:31.616
He said, yeah.

01:30:31.616 --> 01:30:33.240
I felt really guilty
about it because I

01:30:33.240 --> 01:30:35.400
wish I had been able
to give him more.

01:30:35.400 --> 01:30:37.770
And I said you did
everything you could.

01:30:37.770 --> 01:30:39.300
But why weren't the
schools helping?

01:30:39.300 --> 01:30:41.049
Why weren't there any
resources or support

01:30:41.049 --> 01:30:42.720
there to prevent
him from getting

01:30:42.720 --> 01:30:45.120
into gangs in the first place?

01:30:45.120 --> 01:30:46.740
And I said that's
the reason why we

01:30:46.740 --> 01:30:49.680
do the work we do is to try
to fight for people like

01:30:49.680 --> 01:30:53.940
[INAUDIBLE] to say that no,
he needed support policies

01:30:53.940 --> 01:30:56.310
and programs that were there.

01:30:56.310 --> 01:30:59.940
And it was a light
switch moment for my dad.

01:30:59.940 --> 01:31:03.000
And so I see this as
an ongoing conversation

01:31:03.000 --> 01:31:05.910
and as an ongoing journey
for us to continue

01:31:05.910 --> 01:31:07.717
to get to know one another.

01:31:07.717 --> 01:31:09.300
And I look forward
to my conversations

01:31:09.300 --> 01:31:10.924
with him about the
Trump Administration

01:31:10.924 --> 01:31:13.770
and see what happens,
because I really

01:31:13.770 --> 01:31:17.520
do want to know what is on his
heart, and what is on his mind,

01:31:17.520 --> 01:31:19.530
and how he
understands the world,

01:31:19.530 --> 01:31:21.870
and how we can change our
understanding of the world

01:31:21.870 --> 01:31:22.976
together.

